{"title_page": "Flatliners", "text_new": "{{short description|1990 film by Joel Schumacher}}\n{{For|the 2017 remake|Flatliners (2017 film)}}\n{{other uses|flatliner (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Flatliners\n| image          = Flatliners.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[John Alvin]]\n| director       = [[Joel Schumacher]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Michael Douglas]]\n* Rick Bieber\n}}\n| writer         = Peter Filardi\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kiefer Sutherland]]\n* [[Julia Roberts]]\n* [[William Baldwin]]\n* [[Oliver Platt]]\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n}}\n| music          = [[James Newton Howard]]\n| cinematography = [[Jan de Bont]]\n| editing        = Robert Brown\n| studio         = Stonebridge Entertainment<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/AbbrView.aspx?s=&Movie=58508|title=Flatliners|work=[[AFI Feature Film Catalog]]|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released       = {{Film date|1990|08|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 114 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Flatliners#tab=summary|title=Flatliners (1990)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $61.5 million<ref name=BOM/>\n}}\n'''''Flatliners''''' is a 1990 American [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[psychological horror]] film directed by [[Joel Schumacher]], produced by [[Michael Douglas]] and Rick Bieber, and written by Peter Filardi. It stars [[Kiefer Sutherland]], [[Julia Roberts]], [[William Baldwin]], [[Oliver Platt]], and [[Kevin Bacon]]. The film is about five medical students who attempt to find out what lies [[Afterlife|beyond death]] by conducting clandestine experiments that produce [[near-death experience]]s. The film was shot on the campus of [[Loyola University Chicago|Loyola University]] (Chicago) between October 1989 and January 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymoviechannel.com/movies/flatliners/details|title=Flatliners - Sony Movie Channel|website=www.sonymoviechannel.com}}</ref> and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing]] in 1990 ([[Charles L. Campbell]] and [[Richard C. Franklin]]). The film was theatrically released on August 10, 1990, by [[Columbia Pictures]]. It grossed $61 million at the box office.\n\nA [[Flatliners (2017 film)|follow-up]] directed by Danish filmmaker [[Niels Arden Oplev]] was released in September 2017, also featuring Kiefer Sutherland in a starring role.{{efn|A [[deleted scene]] in [[Flatliners (2017 film)|''Flatliners'']] (2017) establishes Sutherland's character \"Dr. Barry Wolfson\" being an older version of Dr. Nelson Wright from the 1990 film, having since changed his name.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ann|title=Kiefer Sutherland reveals who he's playing in the Flatliners reboot|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/07/27/kiefer-sutherland-reveals-who-hes-playing-in-the-flatliners-reboot-6032883/|website=Metro|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=27 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Oplev|first=Niels Arden|title=There\u2019s A Flatliners Deleted Scene That Connects The New Movie To The Original|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1708220/theres-a-flatliners-deleted-scene-that-connects-the-new-movie-to-the-original|website=[[Cinema Blend]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=28 September 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- IMPORTANT NOTICE: Please see WP:FILMPLOT before editing. Plot summaries are recommended to be 400-700 words. -->\nNelson Wright, a medical student, walks onto a beach one day and proclaims \u201ctoday is a good day to die\u201d. He later convinces four of his medical school classmates\u2014Joe Hurley, David Labraccio, Randy Steckle, and Rachel Manus\u2014to help him discover what lies beyond death. Nelson flatlines for one minute before his classmates resuscitate him. While \"dead\", he experiences a sort of afterlife. He sees a vision of a boy he bullied as a child, Billy Mahoney. He merely tells his friends that he cannot describe what he saw, but something is there. The others follow Nelson's daring feat.\n\nJoe flatlines next, and he experiences an erotic afterlife sequence. He agrees with Nelson's claim that something indeed exists. David is third to flatline, and he sees a vision of a girl, Winnie Hicks, whom he bullied in grade school. The three men start to experience hallucinations related to their afterlife visions. Nelson gets physically beat up by Billy Mahoney twice. Joe, engaged to be married, is haunted by his home videos of his sexual dalliances with other women. David finds Winnie Hicks on a train, and she verbally taunts him the way he taunted her.\n\nRachel decides to flatline next on Halloween. David tries to stop the others from giving Rachel their same fate, but she is already \"dead\" when he arrives. Rachel nearly dies for good after the power goes out, and the men are unable to shock her with the [[defibrillator]] paddles. Luckily, she survives, but she, too, is haunted by the memory of her father committing suicide when she was young.\n\nThe three men finally reveal their harrowing experiences to one another, and David decides to put his visions to a stop. Meanwhile, Joe's fianc\u00e9e, Anne, comes to his apartment, and she breaks up with him after she discovers his videos. Joe's visions cease after Anne leaves him.\n\nDavid goes to visit Winnie Hicks, now grown up, and apologizes to her. Winnie accepts his apology and thanks him. David immediately feels a weight lifted off his shoulders. Then, David finds Nelson, who accompanied David to visit Winnie, beating himself with a climbing axe. In Nelson's mind, however, Billy Mahoney is attempting for a third time to beat him to death. David stops him, and they return to town.\n\nRachel seeks comfort in the arms of David, and the two spend the night together. While Rachel and David are together, Nelson takes Steckle and Joe to a graveyard. He reveals that he killed Billy Mahoney as a kid by throwing rocks at him until he fell out of a tree. Nelson storms off, leaving Joe and Steckle stranded.\n\nDavid leaves Rachel alone in order to rescue Joe and Steckle at the cemetery. While alone, Rachel goes to the bathroom, and finds her father. He apologizes to his daughter, and her guilt over his death is lifted when she discovers that he was addicted to heroin. Then, Nelson calls Rachel, and he tells her that he needs to flatline again in order to make amends. He apologizes for involving her and their friends in his stupid plan.\n\nThe three men race to Nelson, who has been dead for an estimated nine minutes already. Rachel soon finds them, and the four friends work feverishly to save Nelson. In the afterlife, Nelson is experiencing himself as a young boy being stoned by Billy Mahoney from the tree. Nelson dies in the afterlife from the fall, and his friends cannot revive him. When they are about to give up, Mahoney forgives Nelson, and David gives Nelson one last shock. This brings him back, and Nelson tells them, \"It wasn't such a good day to die.\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Kiefer Sutherland]] as Nelson Wright\n* [[Julia Roberts]] as Rachel Manus\n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as David Labraccio\n* [[William Baldwin]] as Joe Hurley\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Randy Steckle\n* [[Kimberly Scott]] as Winnie Hicks\n* Joshua Rudoy as Billy Mahoney\n* [[Benjamin Mouton]] as Mr. Manus\n* [[Hope Davis]] as Anne Coldren\n* [[Patricia Belcher]] as Edna\n* [[Beth Grant]] as Housewife\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\n[[Columbia Pictures]] released ''Flatliners'' theatrically  on August 10, 1990.  The film debuted at No.1<ref>{{cite news|title= Postcards Takes No. 1 at Box Office Movies: Mother-daughter comedy sales hit $8.1 million. Paramount's `Ghost' is in second place on $5.8 million in sales.|publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 17, 1990|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-17/entertainment/ca-740_1_ticket-sales|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> and took in $10 million on its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|title= Flatliners Leads Lively Box Office : Movies: Young audience helps medical drama and Gibson's 'Air America' shoot down Nicholson's 'Two Jakes.' |work= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 14, 1990|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-14/entertainment/ca-765_1_air-america|accessdate=2010-11-23|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref>  It grossed $61.5 million total in the United States.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=flatliners.htm|title=Flatliners|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 48% of critics give the film a positive review based on 44 reviews, with the critical consensus \"While it boasts an impressive cast, striking visuals, and an effective mood, ''Flatliners'' never quite jolts its story to life.\"<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/flatliners/ ''Flatliners'', Rotten Tomatoes.] Accessed March 11, 2013.</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average rating to reviews, the film has a score 55 out of 100, based 10 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/flatliners |title=Flatliners|website=[[Metacritic]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 30, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\nIn her review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Caryn James wrote, \"when taken on its own stylish terms, ''Flatliners'' is greatly entertaining. Viewers are likely to go along with this film instantly or else ridicule it to death. Its atmospheric approach doesn't admit much middle ground.\"<ref>James, Caryn. [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE6D91F39F933A2575BC0A966958260 \"Young Doctors Explore the Boundary Between Life and Death\", ''New York Times'' (August 10, 1990).] Accessed May 18, 2009.</ref> Critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised the film as \"an original, intelligent thriller, well-directed by Joel Schumacher\" and called the cast \"talented young actors, [who] inhabit the shadows with the right mixture of intensity, fear and [[Self-confidence|cockiness]]\". But Ebert criticized ''Flatliners'' for \"plot manipulation that is unworthy of the brilliance of its theme. I only wish it had been restructured so we didn't need to go through the same crisis so many times.\"<ref>Ebert, Roger. [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19900810/REVIEWS/8100301/1023 ''Flatliners'' review, ''Chicago Sun-Times'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref> Similarly, [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine praised the film's young stars, but complained that \"by dodging the questions it raises about life after death, ''Flatliners'' ends up tripping on timidity. It's a movie about daring that dares nothing.\"<ref>Travers, Peter. [https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/5948163/review/5948164/flatliners ''Flatliners'' review, ''Rolling Stone'' #584 (Aug. 9, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"D\" rating and [[Owen Gleiberman]] wrote, \"What isn't in evidence is the sort of overheated lunacy that made the [[William Hurt]] speed-freak trip movie ''[[Altered States]]'' (1980) such delectable trash. ''Flatliners'' is [[campy|camp]], but of a very low order. Schumacher is too intent on pandering to the youth market to take the mad risks and plunges that make for a scintillating bad movie.\"<ref>Gleiberman, Owen. [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,317940,00.html''Flatliners'' review. ''Entertainment Weekly'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed January 20, 2010.</ref> In contrast, ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s Rita Kempley loved the film, calling it: \"a heart-stopping, breathtakingly sumptuous haunted house of a movie\".<ref>Kempley, Rita. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/flatlinersrkempley_a0a093.htm''Flatliners'' review. ''Washington Post'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref> The film has become a [[cult film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/news/1540549/the-weird-reason-the-new-flatliners-isnt-really-a-remake|title=The Weird Reason The New Flatliners Isn't Really A Remake|date=1 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n* \"Party Town\" \u2013 Written and performed by [[Dave Stewart and the Spiritual Cowboys]]\n* \"[[The Clapping Song]]\" \u2013 Written by [[Lincoln Chase]]\n\n==Follow-up==\n{{main|Flatliners (2017 film)}}\nOn October 5, 2015, a follow-up starring [[Ellen Page]] and [[Diego Luna]] was announced,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ellen-page-flatliners-remake-julia-roberts-thriller-1201355718/|title=Ellen Page in Talks to Star in \u2018Flatliners\u2019 Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|publisher=Variety|date=2015-10-05 |accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/flatliners-remake-ellen-page-diego-luna-1201718794/|title=Diego Luna in Talks to Join Ellen Page in \u2018Flatliners\u2019 Remake|publisher=Variety|date=2016-02-29 |accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> following the casting of [[Nina Dobrev]], [[James Norton (actor)|James Norton]] and [[Kiersey Clemons]]. Kiefer Sutherland also appears in the remake. Sutherland had originally announced that he was reprising his role as Nelson Wright, revealing that the new film would actually be a sequel rather than a remake. However, upon release, Sutherland's character is identified as Barry Wolfson; a deleted scene indicates Sutherland is in fact playing the same character, living under a new identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spinoff.comicbookresources.com/2016/07/30/new-flatliners-is-actually-a-sequel-kiefer-sutherland-reveals/|title=New 'Flatliners' is Actually a Sequel, Kiefer Sutherland Reveals|date=30 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Directed by Danish filmmaker [[Niels Arden Oplev]], it was released on September 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movie/flatliners-2017|title=Flatliners|work=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[A Thousand Deaths (London short story)|A Thousand Deaths]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0099582}}\n* {{Amg movie|17756}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|id=flatliners}}\n\n{{Joel Schumacher}}\n{{Michael Douglas}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about bullying]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Films about death]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Medical-themed films]]\n[[Category:Near-death experiences in fiction]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural thriller films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by James Newton Howard]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Joel Schumacher]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Douglas]]\n[[Category:Films set in universities and colleges]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the 2017 remake|Flatliners (2017 film)}}\n{{other uses|flatliner (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Flatliners\n| image          = Flatliners.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[John Alvin]]\n| director       = [[Joel Schumacher]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Michael Douglas]]\n* Rick Bieber\n}}\n| writer         = Peter Filardi\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Kiefer Sutherland]]\n* [[Julia Roberts]]\n* [[William Baldwin]]\n* [[Oliver Platt]]\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n}}\n| music          = [[James Newton Howard]]\n| cinematography = [[Jan de Bont]]\n| editing        = Robert Brown\n| studio         = Stonebridge Entertainment<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/AbbrView.aspx?s=&Movie=58508|title=Flatliners|work=[[AFI Feature Film Catalog]]|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released       = {{Film date|1990|08|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 114 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Flatliners#tab=summary|title=Flatliners (1990)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $61.5 million<ref name=BOM/>\n}}\n'''''Flatliners''''' is a 1990 American [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[psychological horror]] film directed by [[Joel Schumacher]], produced by [[Michael Douglas]] and Rick Bieber, and written by Peter Filardi. It stars [[Kiefer Sutherland]], [[Julia Roberts]], [[William Baldwin]], [[Oliver Platt]], and [[Kevin Bacon]]. The film is about five medical students who attempt to find out what lies [[Afterlife|beyond death]] by conducting clandestine experiments that produce [[near-death experience]]s. The film was shot on the campus of [[Loyola University Chicago|Loyola University]] (Chicago) between October 1989 and January 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymoviechannel.com/movies/flatliners/details|title=Flatliners - Sony Movie Channel|website=www.sonymoviechannel.com}}</ref> and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing]] in 1990 ([[Charles L. Campbell]] and [[Richard C. Franklin]]). The film was theatrically released on August 10, 1990, by [[Columbia Pictures]]. It grossed $61 million at the box office.\n\nA [[Flatliners (2017 film)|follow-up]] directed by Danish filmmaker [[Niels Arden Oplev]] was released in September 2017, also featuring Kiefer Sutherland in a starring role.{{efn|A [[deleted scene]] in [[Flatliners (2017 film)|''Flatliners'']] (2017) establishes Sutherland's character \"Dr. Barry Wolfson\" being an older version of Dr. Nelson Wright from the 1990 film, having since changed his name.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Ann|title=Kiefer Sutherland reveals who he's playing in the Flatliners reboot|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/07/27/kiefer-sutherland-reveals-who-hes-playing-in-the-flatliners-reboot-6032883/|website=Metro|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=27 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Oplev|first=Niels Arden|title=There\u2019s A Flatliners Deleted Scene That Connects The New Movie To The Original|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1708220/theres-a-flatliners-deleted-scene-that-connects-the-new-movie-to-the-original|website=[[Cinema Blend]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=28 September 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- IMPORTANT NOTICE: Please see WP:FILMPLOT before editing. Plot summaries are recommended to be 400-700 words. -->\nNelson Wright, a medical student, walks onto a beach one day and proclaims \u201ctoday is a good day to die\u201d. He later convinces four of his medical school classmates\u2014Joe Hurley, David Labraccio, Randy Steckle, and Rachel Manus\u2014to help him discover what lies beyond death. Nelson flatlines for one minute before his classmates resuscitate him. While \"dead\", he experiences a sort of afterlife. He sees a vision of a boy he bullied as a child, Billy Mahoney. He merely tells his friends that he cannot describe what he saw, but something is there. The others follow Nelson's daring feat.\n\nJoe flatlines next, and he experiences an erotic afterlife sequence. He agrees with Nelson's claim that something indeed exists. David is third to flatline, and he sees a vision of a girl, Winnie Hicks, whom he bullied in grade school. The three men start to experience hallucinations related to their afterlife visions. Nelson gets physically beat up by Billy Mahoney twice. Joe, engaged to be married, is haunted by his home videos of his sexual dalliances with other women. David finds Winnie Hicks on a train, and she verbally taunts him the way he taunted her.\n\nRachel decides to flatline next on Halloween. David tries to stop the others from giving Rachel their same fate, but she is already \"dead\" when he arrives. Rachel nearly dies for good after the power goes out, and the men are unable to shock her with the [[defibrillator]] paddles. Luckily, she survives, but she, too, is haunted by the memory of her father committing suicide when she was young.\n\nThe three men finally reveal their harrowing experiences to one another, and David decides to put his visions to a stop. Meanwhile, Joe's fianc\u00e9e, Anne, comes to his apartment, and she breaks up with him after she discovers his videos. Joe's visions cease after Anne leaves him.\n\nDavid goes to visit Winnie Hicks, now grown up, and apologizes to her. Winnie accepts his apology and thanks him. David immediately feels a weight lifted off his shoulders. Then, David finds Nelson, who accompanied David to visit Winnie, beating himself with a climbing axe. In Nelson's mind, however, Billy Mahoney is attempting for a third time to beat him to death. David stops him, and they return to town.\n\nRachel seeks comfort in the arms of David, and the two spend the night together. While Rachel and David are together, Nelson takes Steckle and Joe to a graveyard. He reveals that he killed Billy Mahoney as a kid by throwing rocks at him until he fell out of a tree. Nelson storms off, leaving Joe and Steckle stranded.\n\nDavid leaves Rachel alone in order to rescue Joe and Steckle at the cemetery. While alone, Rachel goes to the bathroom, and finds her father. He apologizes to his daughter, and her guilt over his death is lifted when she discovers that he was addicted to heroin. Then, Nelson calls Rachel, and he tells her that he needs to flatline again in order to make amends. He apologizes for involving her and their friends in his stupid plan.\n\nThe three men race to Nelson, who has been dead for an estimated nine minutes already. Rachel soon finds them, and the four friends work feverishly to save Nelson. In the afterlife, Nelson is experiencing himself as a young boy being stoned by Billy Mahoney from the tree. Nelson dies in the afterlife from the fall, and his friends cannot revive him. When they are about to give up, Mahoney forgives Nelson, and David gives Nelson one last shock. This brings him back, and Nelson tells them, \"It wasn't such a good day to die.\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Kiefer Sutherland]] as Nelson Wright\n* [[Julia Roberts]] as Rachel Manus\n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as David Labraccio\n* [[William Baldwin]] as Joe Hurley\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Randy Steckle\n* [[Kimberly Scott]] as Winnie Hicks\n* Joshua Rudoy as Billy Mahoney\n* [[Benjamin Mouton]] as Mr. Manus\n* [[Hope Davis]] as Anne Coldren\n* [[Patricia Belcher]] as Edna\n* [[Beth Grant]] as Housewife\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Release==\n[[Columbia Pictures]] released ''Flatliners'' theatrically  on August 10, 1990.  The film debuted at No.1<ref>{{cite news|title= Postcards Takes No. 1 at Box Office Movies: Mother-daughter comedy sales hit $8.1 million. Paramount's `Ghost' is in second place on $5.8 million in sales.|publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 17, 1990|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-17/entertainment/ca-740_1_ticket-sales|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> and took in $10 million on its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|title= Flatliners Leads Lively Box Office : Movies: Young audience helps medical drama and Gibson's 'Air America' shoot down Nicholson's 'Two Jakes.' |work= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 14, 1990|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-14/entertainment/ca-765_1_air-america|accessdate=2010-11-23|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref>  It grossed $61.5 million total in the United States.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=flatliners.htm|title=Flatliners|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 48% of critics give the film a positive review based on 44 reviews, with the critical consensus \"While it boasts an impressive cast, striking visuals, and an effective mood, ''Flatliners'' never quite jolts its story to life.\"<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/flatliners/ ''Flatliners'', Rotten Tomatoes.] Accessed March 11, 2013.</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average rating to reviews, the film has a score 55 out of 100, based 10 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/flatliners |title=Flatliners|website=[[Metacritic]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 30, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\nIn her review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Caryn James wrote, \"when taken on its own stylish terms, ''Flatliners'' is greatly entertaining. Viewers are likely to go along with this film instantly or else ridicule it to death. Its atmospheric approach doesn't admit much middle ground.\"<ref>James, Caryn. [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE6D91F39F933A2575BC0A966958260 \"Young Doctors Explore the Boundary Between Life and Death\", ''New York Times'' (August 10, 1990).] Accessed May 18, 2009.</ref> Critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised the film as \"an original, intelligent thriller, well-directed by Joel Schumacher\" and called the cast \"talented young actors, [who] inhabit the shadows with the right mixture of intensity, fear and [[Self-confidence|cockiness]]\". But Ebert criticized ''Flatliners'' for \"plot manipulation that is unworthy of the brilliance of its theme. I only wish it had been restructured so we didn't need to go through the same crisis so many times.\"<ref>Ebert, Roger. [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19900810/REVIEWS/8100301/1023 ''Flatliners'' review, ''Chicago Sun-Times'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref> Similarly, [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine praised the film's young stars, but complained that \"by dodging the questions it raises about life after death, ''Flatliners'' ends up tripping on timidity. It's a movie about daring that dares nothing.\"<ref>Travers, Peter. [https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/5948163/review/5948164/flatliners ''Flatliners'' review, ''Rolling Stone'' #584 (Aug. 9, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"D\" rating and [[Owen Gleiberman]] wrote, \"What isn't in evidence is the sort of overheated lunacy that made the [[William Hurt]] speed-freak trip movie ''[[Altered States]]'' (1980) such delectable trash. ''Flatliners'' is [[campy|camp]], but of a very low order. Schumacher is too intent on pandering to the youth market to take the mad risks and plunges that make for a scintillating bad movie.\"<ref>Gleiberman, Owen. [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,317940,00.html''Flatliners'' review. ''Entertainment Weekly'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed January 20, 2010.</ref> In contrast, ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s Rita Kempley loved the film, calling it: \"a heart-stopping, breathtakingly sumptuous haunted house of a movie\".<ref>Kempley, Rita. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/flatlinersrkempley_a0a093.htm''Flatliners'' review. ''Washington Post'' (Aug. 10, 1990).] Accessed Mar. 26, 2009.</ref> The film has become a [[cult film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/news/1540549/the-weird-reason-the-new-flatliners-isnt-really-a-remake|title=The Weird Reason The New Flatliners Isn't Really A Remake|date=1 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n* \"Party Town\" \u2013 Written and performed by [[Dave Stewart and the Spiritual Cowboys]]\n* \"[[The Clapping Song]]\" \u2013 Written by [[Lincoln Chase]]\n\n==Follow-up==\n{{main|Flatliners (2017 film)}}\nOn October 5, 2015, a follow-up starring [[Ellen Page]] and [[Diego Luna]] was announced,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ellen-page-flatliners-remake-julia-roberts-thriller-1201355718/|title=Ellen Page in Talks to Star in \u2018Flatliners\u2019 Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|publisher=Variety|date=2015-10-05 |accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/flatliners-remake-ellen-page-diego-luna-1201718794/|title=Diego Luna in Talks to Join Ellen Page in \u2018Flatliners\u2019 Remake|publisher=Variety|date=2016-02-29 |accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> following the casting of [[Nina Dobrev]], [[James Norton (actor)|James Norton]] and [[Kiersey Clemons]]. Kiefer Sutherland also appears in the remake. Sutherland had originally announced that he was reprising his role as Nelson Wright, revealing that the new film would actually be a sequel rather than a remake. However, upon release, Sutherland's character is identified as Barry Wolfson; a deleted scene indicates Sutherland is in fact playing the same character, living under a new identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spinoff.comicbookresources.com/2016/07/30/new-flatliners-is-actually-a-sequel-kiefer-sutherland-reveals/|title=New 'Flatliners' is Actually a Sequel, Kiefer Sutherland Reveals|date=30 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Directed by Danish filmmaker [[Niels Arden Oplev]], it was released on September 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movie/flatliners-2017|title=Flatliners|work=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[A Thousand Deaths (London short story)|A Thousand Deaths]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0099582}}\n* {{Amg movie|17756}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|id=flatliners}}\n\n{{Joel Schumacher}}\n{{Michael Douglas}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about bullying]]\n[[Category:Films about Christianity]]\n[[Category:Films about death]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Medical-themed films]]\n[[Category:Near-death experiences in fiction]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural thriller films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by James Newton Howard]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Joel Schumacher]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael Douglas]]\n[[Category:Films set in universities and colleges]]\n", "name_user": "Ayenaee", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"1990 film by Joel Schumacher\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flatliners"}
