{"title_page": "Francine Larrimore", "text_new": "{{sources|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Francine Larrimore\n| image = Francine Larrimore.JPG\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = ''Munsey's Magazine'', 1918\n| birth_name = Francine La Remee\n| birth_date = August 22, 1898\n| birth_place =[[Verdun]], France\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1975|3|7|1898|8|22}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| restingplace =\n| othername =\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1910\u20131939\n| spouse = [[Con Conrad]]<br>Alfred T. Mannon\n| children =\n| parents =\n}}\n'''Francine Larrimore''' (August 22, 1898 &ndash; March 7, 1975) was a stage and screen actress.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in France, Larrimore came to the United States when a child. Her parents were J. Louis La Remee and Sarah Adler, a sister of the Yiddish stage star [[Jacob Pavlovich Adler|Jacob Adler]] and not to be confused with Jacob's third wife also named Sara.<ref>''Great Stars of the American Stage'' by Daniel Blum c. 1952 ''Profile #82''</ref><ref>[http://broadway.cas.sc.edu/content/francine-larrimore Broadway Photographs, University of South Carolina] Retrieved July 13, 2016</ref> Jacob's children [[Stella Adler|Stella]] and [[Luther Adler|Luther]] are her cousins. Her sister Stella Larrimore (1905\u20131960) was married to the stage and screen star [[Robert Warwick]].\n\nLarrimore began her stage career in 1910. In 1926 she created the role of Roxie Hart in the Broadway premiere of ''Chicago''. She played Theodora Gloucester in the 1921 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] comedy ''[[Nice People (play)|Nice People]]''. She also appeared in ''Let Us Be Gay''and ''Brief Moment''. She was part of a radio program called ''Grand Central Station'', in 1941.<ref>https://rmoa.unm.edu/docviewer.php?docId=wyu-ah05976.xml</ref>\n\nShe appeared in a string of silent films in the 1910s, i.e. ''The Devil's Darling'' (1915, Mutual), ''The Princess From The Poorhouse'' aka ''[[The Royal Pauper]]'' (1917, Edison) and ''[[Max Wants a Divorce]]'' (1917, Essanay) co-starring [[Max Linder]]. Most are now considered [[lost film]]s.\n\nHer sound films number just two. She disappeared from acting in 1939.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[A Woman's Resurrection]]'' (1915) (*probably her debut billed as ''Frances Lorrimore'')\n*''The Devil's Darling'' (1915) *short\n*''[[The Royal Pauper]]'' (1917)\n*''[[Max Wants a Divorce]]'' (1917) *short\n*''Max in a Taxi'' (1917) *short\n*''Somewhere in America'' (1917)\n*''[[John Meade's Woman]]'' (1937)\n*''[[The Devil's Daughter (1939 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'' (1939)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Francine Larrimore}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*{{IMDb name|0488633}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8036371|Francine Larrimore}}\n*[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%93&keywords=francine+larrimore Francine Larrimore] portrait gallery NY Public Library\n*[http://broadway.cas.sc.edu/index.php?action=showPerformer&id=4 Francine Larrimore biography]\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/search/collection/sayre/searchterm/francine%20larrimore/field/all/mode/all/conn/and/cosuppress/ early portraits](Univ. of Washington, Sayre Collection)\n* The [https://rmoa.unm.edu/docviewer.php?docId=wyu-ah05976.xml Francine Larrimore papers] at the [http://www.uwyo.edu/ahc/ American Heritage Center]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Larrimore, Francine}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Verdun]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{sources|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Francine Larrimore\n| image = Francine Larrimore.JPG\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = ''Munsey's Magazine'', 1918\n| birth_name = Francine La Remee\n| birth_date = August 22, 1898\n| birth_place =[[Verdun]], France\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1975|3|7|1898|8|22}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| restingplace =\n| othername =\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1910\u20131939\n| spouse = [[Con Conrad]]<br>Alfred T. Mannon\n| children =\n| parents =\n}}\n'''Francine Larrimore''' (August 22, 1898 &ndash; March 7, 1975) was a stage and screen actress.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in France, Larrimore came to the United States when a child. Her parents were J. Louis La Remee and Sarah Adler, a sister of the Yiddish stage star [[Jacob Pavlovich Adler|Jacob Adler]] and not to be confused with Jacob's third wife also named Sara.<ref>''Great Stars of the American Stage'' by Daniel Blum c. 1952 ''Profile #82''</ref><ref>[http://broadway.cas.sc.edu/content/francine-larrimore Broadway Photographs, University of South Carolina] Retrieved July 13, 2016</ref> Jacob's children [[Stella Adler|Stella]] and [[Luther Adler|Luther]] are her cousins. Her sister Stella Larrimore (1905\u20131960) was married to the stage and screen star [[Robert Warwick]].\n\nLarrimore began her stage career in 1910. In 1926 she created the role of Roxie Hart in the Broadway premiere of ''Chicago''. She played Theodora Gloucester in the 1921 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] comedy ''[[Nice People (play)|Nice People]]''.\nShe appeared in a string of silent films in the 1910s, i.e. ''The Devil's Darling'' (1915, Mutual), ''The Princess From The Poorhouse'' aka ''[[The Royal Pauper]]'' (1917, Edison) and ''[[Max Wants a Divorce]]'' (1917, Essanay) co-starring [[Max Linder]]. Most are now considered [[lost film]]s.\n\nHer sound films number just two. She disappeared from acting in 1939.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[A Woman's Resurrection]]'' (1915) (*probably her debut billed as ''Frances Lorrimore'')\n*''The Devil's Darling'' (1915) *short\n*''[[The Royal Pauper]]'' (1917)\n*''[[Max Wants a Divorce]]'' (1917) *short\n*''Max in a Taxi'' (1917) *short\n*''Somewhere in America'' (1917)\n*''[[John Meade's Woman]]'' (1937)\n*''[[The Devil's Daughter (1939 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'' (1939)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Francine Larrimore}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*{{IMDb name|0488633}}\n*{{Find a Grave|8036371|Francine Larrimore}}\n*[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%93&keywords=francine+larrimore Francine Larrimore] portrait gallery NY Public Library\n*[http://broadway.cas.sc.edu/index.php?action=showPerformer&id=4 Francine Larrimore biography]\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/search/collection/sayre/searchterm/francine%20larrimore/field/all/mode/all/conn/and/cosuppress/ early portraits](Univ. of Washington, Sayre Collection)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Larrimore, Francine}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Verdun]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ACardin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added information about plays and radio program", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francine_Larrimore"}
{"title_page": "Aluminium foil", "text_new": "{{about|aluminium foil|other types of foil|Foil (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n<!-- Please DO NOT unnecessarily change Aluminium to Aluminum. For more information, see [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style#National varieties of English]]-->\n[[File:Aluminium cooking foil.jpg|thumb|200px|A sheet of aluminium foil]]\n'''Aluminium foil''(often erroneously called '''[[tin foil]]''') is [[aluminium]] prepared in thin [[metal leaf|metal leaves]] with a thickness less than {{convert|0.2|mm|mil|abbr=on}}; thinner gauges down to {{convert|6|micrometre|mil}} are also commonly used.<ref name=\"EAFA facts1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.alufoil.org/facts.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325000221/http://www.alufoil.org/facts.html |archivedate=2016-03-25 }}</ref> In the United States, foils are commonly gauged in thousandths of an inch or [[Thousandth of an inch|mils]]. Standard household foil is typically {{convert|0.016|mm|mil|abbr=on}} thick, and heavy duty household foil is typically {{convert|0.024|mm|mil|abbr=on}}. The [[Foil (metal)|foil]] is pliable, and can be readily bent or wrapped around objects. Thin foils are fragile and are sometimes [[laminate]]d to other materials such as [[plastic]]s or [[paper]] to make them more useful. Aluminium foil supplanted [[tin foil]] in the mid 20th century.\n\nAnnual production of aluminium foil was approximately {{convert|800,000|tonne}} in Europe<ref name=\"EAFA facts1\"/> and {{convert|600,000|tonne}} in the U.S. in 2003.<ref name=aausa>[http://www.aluminum.org/Content/ContentGroups/Tech_Q_and_A/New_Aluminum_Foil_Manual_Covers_It_All.htm Aluminum Association (USA)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227184227/http://www.aluminum.org/Content/ContentGroups/Tech_Q_and_A/New_Aluminum_Foil_Manual_Covers_It_All.htm |date=2007-12-27 }}</ref> Approximately 75% of aluminium foil is used for [[packaging]] of [[food]]s, [[cosmetics]], and chemical products, and 25% is used for industrial applications (e.g., thermal insulation, cables, and electronics).<ref name=aausa/> It can be [[Aluminium recycling|recycled]].\n \nIn [[North America]], aluminium foil is known as \"aluminum foil\". It was popularised by [[Reynolds Metals]], the leading manufacturer in North America. In the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]] it is, informally, widely called tin foil, for historical reasons (similar to how [[steel can]]s are often still called \"[[tin can]]s\"). [[Metallised film]]s are sometimes mistaken for aluminium foil, but are actually polymer films [[thin-film deposition|coated]] with a thin layer of aluminium. In [[Australia]], aluminium foil is widely called alfoil.\n\n== History ==\n\n===Before aluminium foil===\nFoil made from a thin leaf of [[tin]] was commercially available before its aluminium counterpart. [[Tin foil]] was marketed commercially from the late nineteenth into the early twentieth century.  The term \"tin foil\" survives in the English language as a term for the newer aluminium foil. Tin foil is less [[ductility|malleable]] than aluminium foil and tends to give a slight tin taste to food wrapped in it.  Tin foil has been supplanted by aluminium and other materials for wrapping food.<ref>{{cite web |last=Berger |first=Kenneth R. |title=A Brief History of Packaging |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/IR00001524/00001 |publisher=University of Florida |accessdate=24 September 2014 |date=December 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909204256/http://ufdc.ufl.edu/IR00001524/00001 |archivedate=9 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe first audio recordings on [[phonograph cylinders]] were made on tin foil.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tinfoil Recordings |url=http://cylinders.library.ucsb.edu/history-tinfoil.php |work=Cylinder Recordings: A Primer |publisher=University of California at Santa Barbara |accessdate=17 October 2011 |author=Cylinder Preservation and Digitization Project, UCSB |format=web page |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016155323/http://cylinders.library.ucsb.edu/history-tinfoil.php |archivedate=16 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===The first aluminium foil===\nTin was first replaced by aluminium in 1910, when the first aluminium foil rolling plant, \"Dr. Lauber, Neher & Cie.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Mary Bellis |url=http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/blaluminum.htm |title=Charles Martin Hall - The History of Aluminum |publisher=Inventors.about.com |date=2012-04-09 |accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref> was opened in [[Kreuzlingen|Emmishofen]], [[Switzerland]]. The plant, owned by J.G. Neher & Sons, the aluminium manufacturers, started in 1886 in [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland, at the foot of the [[Rhine Falls]], capturing the falls' energy to process aluminium. Neher's sons, together with Dr. Lauber, discovered the endless rolling process and the use of aluminium foil as a protective barrier in December 1907.\n\nIn 1911, Bern-based Tobler began wrapping its chocolate bars in aluminium foil, including the unique [[Triangular prism|triangular]] chocolate bar, [[Toblerone]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.alufoil.org/history.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512075406/http://www.alufoil.org/history.html|archivedate=2015-05-12}}</ref> By 1912, aluminium foil was being used by [[Maggi]] (today a Nestl\u00e9 brand) to pack soups and stock cubes.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} \n\nThe first use of foil in the United States was in 1913 for wrapping [[Life Savers]], candy bars, and gum.<ref name=\"Hanlon\">Hanlon, J. (1992). 1st ed. Handbook of Package Engineering, Lancaster, Pennsylvania, and Technomic Publishing: {{ISBN|0-87762-924-2}}. Chapter 3 Films and Foils.</ref> Processes evolved over time to include the use of print, colour, lacquer, laminate and the [[Embossing (manufacturing)|embossing]] of the aluminium.\n\n== Manufacture ==\n[[File:Aluminium foil micrometer.jpg|thumb|250px|A roll of aluminium foil, with [[micrometer]] showing a thickness of {{convert|13|\u00b5m|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}]]\n{{see also|Rolling (metalworking)}}\n\nAluminium foil is produced by rolling sheet [[ingots]] cast from molten [[Aluminium#Production and refinement|billet aluminium]], then re-rolling on sheet and foil rolling mills to the desired thickness, or by continuously casting and cold rolling. To maintain a constant thickness in aluminium foil production, [[beta radiation]] is passed through the foil to a sensor on the other side. If the intensity becomes too high, then the rollers adjust, increasing the thickness. If the intensities become too low and the foil has become too thick, the rollers apply more pressure, causing the foil to be made thinner.\n\nThe continuous casting method is much less energy intensive and has become the preferred process.<ref name=\"Robertson\">Robertson, G. (2006). 2nd ed. Food Packaging, Principles and Practise, Boca Raton, FL, Taylor & Francis Group: {{ISBN|0-8493-3775-5}}. Chapter 7 Metal Packaging Materials.</ref> For thicknesses below {{convert|0.025|mm|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}, two layers are usually put together for the final pass and afterwards separated which produces foil with one bright side and one matte side.<ref name=degarmo/> The two sides in contact with each other are matte and the exterior sides become bright; this is done to reduce tearing, increase production rates, control thickness, and get around the need for a smaller diameter roller.<ref name=degarmo>{{Cite book | last = Degarmo | first = E. Paul | last2 = Black | first2 = J T. | last3 = Kohser | first3 = Ronald A. | title = Materials and Processes in Manufacturing | publisher = Wiley | page = 386 | year = 2003 | edition = 9th | isbn = 0-471-65653-4}}</ref>\n\nSome [[lubrication]] is needed during the rolling stages; otherwise, the foil surface can become marked with a [[herringbone pattern]]. These lubricants are sprayed on the foil surface before passing through the mill rolls. [[Kerosene]] based lubricants are commonly used, although oils approved for food contact must be used for foil intended for food packaging.\n\nAluminium becomes work hardened during the cold rolling process and is [[annealing (metallurgy)|annealed]] for most purposes. The rolls of foil are heated until the degree of softness is reached, which may be up to {{convert|340|C}} for 12 hours. During this heating, the lubricating oils are burned off, leaving a dry surface. Lubricant oils may not be completely burnt off for hard temper rolls, which can make subsequent coating or printing more difficult.\n\nThe rolls of aluminium foil are then slit on [[slitter|slitter rewinding]] machines into smaller rolls. Roll slitting and rewinding is an essential part of the finishing process.\n\n== Properties ==\n[[File:Rubber with sodium silicate beads 6 alu backside.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[photomicrograph|Microscopic close-up]] of aluminium foil on the back of an [[intumescent]] rubber strip.]]\n\nAluminium foils thicker than {{convert|25|\u00b5m|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} are impermeable to oxygen and water. Foils thinner than this become slightly permeable due to minute pinholes caused by the production process.\n\nAluminium foil has a shiny side and a matte side. The shiny side is produced when the aluminium is rolled during the final pass. It is difficult to produce rollers with a gap fine enough to cope with the foil gauge, therefore, for the final pass, two sheets are rolled at the same time, doubling the thickness of the gauge at entry to the rollers. When the sheets are later separated, the inside surface is dull, and the outside surface is shiny. This difference in the finish has led to the perception that favouring a side has an effect when cooking. While many believe (wrongly) that the different properties keep heat out when wrapped with the shiny finish facing out, and keep heat in with the shiny finish facing inwards, the actual difference is imperceptible without instrumentation. Increased reflectivity decreases both absorption and [[Black-body_radiation|emission]] of radiation. Foil may have a non-stick coating on only one side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reynoldskitchens.com/media/10246730/reynolds_wrap_faq.pdf |title=Frequently Asked Questions |accessdate=2014-08-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021084635/http://www.reynoldskitchens.com/media/10246730/reynolds_wrap_faq.pdf |archivedate=2014-10-21 }}</ref> The [[reflectivity]] of bright aluminium foil is 88% while dull embossed foil is about 80%.<ref name=\"Hanlon\"/>\n\n==Uses==\n\n=== Packaging ===\n[[File:Reese's peanut butter cups.jpg|thumb|250px|Chocolates in aluminium foil packaging]]\n\nAluminium is used for packaging as it is highly malleable: it can be easily converted to thin sheets and folded, rolled or packed. Aluminium foil acts as a total barrier to light and oxygen (which cause fats to oxidise or become rancid), odours and flavours, moistness, and germs, and so it is used broadly in food and pharmaceutical packaging, including long-life packs ([[aseptic processing|aseptic packaging]]) for drinks and dairy goods, which allows storing without refrigeration. Aluminium foil containers and trays are used to bake pies and to pack [[Take-out|takeaway]] meals, ready snacks and long life [[pet]] foods.\n\nAluminium foil is widely sold into the [[consumer]] market, often in rolls of {{convert|500|mm|abbr=on}} width and several metres in length.<ref>[http://www.reynoldspkg.com/reynoldskitchens/en/product_category.asp?cat_id=1337 Examples of products]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218165509/http://www.reynoldspkg.com/reynoldskitchens/en/product_category.asp?cat_id=1337 |date=2008-12-18 }}</ref> It is used for wrapping food in order to preserve it, for example, when storing leftover food in a [[refrigerator]] (where it serves the additional purpose of preventing odour exchange), when taking [[sandwich]]es on a journey, when baking, or when selling some kinds of [[take-away]] or [[fast food]]. [[Tex-Mex]] restaurants in the [[United States]], for example, typically provide take-away [[burrito]]s wrapped in aluminium foil.\n\n=== Insulation ===\nAluminium foil is widely used for radiation shield (barrier and reflectivity), heat exchangers ([[heat conduction]]) and cable liners (barrier and [[electrical conductivity]]). Aluminium foil's heat conductive qualities make it a common accessory in [[hookah]] smoking: a sheet of perforated aluminium foil is frequently placed between the coal and the tobacco, allowing the tobacco to be heated without coming into direct contact with the burning coal.\n\n=== Electromagnetic shielding ===\nThe [[Electromagnetic shielding|shielding effectiveness]] of aluminium foil depends upon the type of incident field (electric, magnetic, or plane wave), the thickness of the foil, and the frequency (which determines the [[skin depth]]). Shielding effectiveness is usually broken down into a reflection loss (the energy bounces off the shield rather than penetrates it) and an absorption loss (the energy is dissipated within the shield).\n\nAlthough aluminium is non-magnetic, it is a good conductor, so even a thin sheet reflects almost all of an incident electric wave. At frequencies more than 100&nbsp;MHz, the ''transmitted'' electric field is attenuated by more than 80 [[decibel]]s (dB) (less than 10<sup>\u22128</sup> = 0.00000001 of the power gets through) <ref>{{Citation |last=Ott |first=Henry |title=Noise Reduction Techniques in Electronic Systems |year=1976 |publisher=Wiley Interscience |isbn=0-471-65726-3 |doi= }}. {{Harvtxt|Ott|1976|loc=figure 6-13}} graphs reflection loss for copper, and shows electric field and plane wave losses at greater than 90&nbsp;dB.</ref> -- however actual energy absorption is minimal:  the remaining high-frequency rf energy is almost perfectly reflected from uniform flat aluminium surface, and thus, reflected signal may continue to propagate internally, and if holes or passages of suitable geometry exist in the shield, signal propagation may continue out through those, the aluminium being good material for implementation of a microwave-frequency [[waveguide]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nThin sheets of aluminium are not very effective at attenuating low-frequency magnetic fields.  The shielding effectiveness is dependent upon the skin depth. A field travelling through one skin depth will lose about 63 per cent of its energy (it is attenuated to 1/e = 1/2.718... of its original energy).  Thin shields also have internal reflections that reduce the shielding effectiveness.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ott|1976|pp=155&ndash;156}}</ref>  For effective shielding from a magnetic field, the shield should be several skin depths thick.  Aluminium foil is about {{convert|1|mil|um}}; a thickness of {{convert|10|mil|um}} (ten times thicker) offers less than 1&nbsp;dB of shielding at 1&nbsp;kHz, about 8&nbsp;dB at 10&nbsp;kHz, and about 25&nbsp;dB at 100&nbsp;kHz.  At these frequencies a [[Ferromagnetism|ferromagnetic material]] such as [[mild steel]] is much more effective, due to different and complementary [[Permeability_(electromagnetism)|electromagnetic permeability]] properties, and common practical shielding implementations utilise both an inner high-frequency reflective material such as aluminium, preferably bonded (via [[Annealing (metallurgy)|annealing]] or [[electroplating]], done to avoid capacitance between separated layers), to a more substantial structural ferromagnetic shell, usually mild steel (in specialized applications, more expensive, less structurally useful and less workable materials may be preferred.)  Despite the relative low mass density of aluminium, this design is usually both lighter and more effective than an equivalently absorptive design utilizing aluminium alone (although with poorer heat dissipative properties, typically accommodated by improved ventilation, which itself needs careful consideration in order to preserve the desired shielding effectiveness).{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n=== Cooking ===\nAluminium foil is also used for [[barbecue|barbecuing]] delicate foods,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zXm8ccnB0P8C&pg=PA207&dq=Aluminium+foil+is+used+for+barbecuing+delicate+foods&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjkLH6r9nUAhUI6mMKHdTmBmEQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=Aluminium%20foil%20is%20used%20for%20barbecuing%20delicate%20foods&f=false|title=Kitchen on Fire!: Mastering the Art of Cooking in 12 Weeks (or Less)|last=Said|first=Olivier|last2=MikeC|first2=Chef|date=2011-11-22|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=9780738214535|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022234134/https://books.google.com/books?id=zXm8ccnB0P8C&pg=PA207&dq=Aluminium+foil+is+used+for+barbecuing+delicate+foods&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjkLH6r9nUAhUI6mMKHdTmBmEQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=Aluminium%20foil%20is%20used%20for%20barbecuing%20delicate%20foods&f=false|archivedate=2017-10-22}}</ref> such as mushrooms and vegetables. Using this method, sometimes called a '''hobo pack''', food is wrapped in foil, then placed on the grill, preventing loss of moisture that may result in a less appealing texture.\n\nAs is the case with all metallic items, aluminium foil reacts to being placed in a [[microwave oven]]. This is because of the [[electromagnetic field]]s of the microwaves inducing electric currents in the foil and high [[voltage|potentials]] at the sharp points of the foil sheet; if the potential is sufficiently high, it will cause [[electric arc]]ing to areas with lower potential, even to the air surrounding the sheet.  Modern microwave ovens have been designed to prevent damage to the [[cavity magnetron]] tube from microwave energy reflection, and aluminium packages designed for microwave heating are available.<ref>Huss, G. (1997) Microwaveable Packaging and Dual-Ovenable Materials in The Wiley Encyclopedia of Packaging Technology, 2nd ed., edited by Brody, A. and Marsch, K. New York, John Wiley and Sons</ref>\n\n=== Art and decoration ===\nHeavier foils made of aluminium are used for art, decoration, and crafts, especially in bright metallic colours. Metallic aluminium, normally silvery in colour, can be made to take on other colours through [[anodization|anodisation]]. Anodising creates an oxide layer on the aluminium surface that can accept coloured dyes or metallic salts, depending on the process used. In this way, aluminium is used to create an inexpensive gold foil that actually contains no gold, and many other bright metallic colours. These foils are sometimes used in distinctive packaging.\n\n=== Geochemical sampling ===\nFoil is used by organic/petroleum geochemists for protecting rock samples taken from the fields and in the labs where the sample is subject to [[biomarker]] analysis. While plastic or cloth bags are normally used for a geological sampling exercise, cloth bags are permeable and may allow organic solvents or oils (such as oils imparted from the skin) to taint the sample, and traces of the plastics from plastic bags may also taint the sample. Foil provides a seal to the ingress of organic solvents and does not taint the sample. Foil is also used extensively in geochemical laboratories to provide a barrier for the geochemist, and for sample storage.\n\n=== Ribbon microphones ===\nThe material used in many [[ribbon microphone]]s is aluminium leaf, or \"[[Metal leaf|imitation silver leaf]]\", as it is sometimes called. This is pure aluminium and is around 0.6 to 2.0 micrometres thick. It is virtually the same material that the BBC used on [[Coles 4038|Coles ribbon]]s, with the exception that they also hand beat the leaf even thinner. They did this by sandwiching the ribbon between toilet paper and beating with a [[ball-peen hammer]]. This \"cold forges\" the leaf. The aluminium leaf was then annealed for an hour in an oven to restore flexibility. Corrugations must also be imparted into the ribbon: Coles used 25 per inch (1&nbsp;mm cycle). RCA 44BX has 19 corrugations per inch (0.7&nbsp;mm cycle) and is around {{convert|50|mm|abbr=on}} long; RCA 77 has 13 corrugations per inch (0.5&nbsp;mm cycle). RCA ribbon material is around 1 to 1.5 micrometres (0.00005&nbsp;inch) thick. The new Nady ribbon plus AEA both state that they use 2 micrometre aluminium ribbon in their microphones.{{Vague|date=March 2013}}\n\n== Environmental issues ==\n{{See also|Aluminium recycling}}\n\nSome aluminium foil products can be [[recycling|recycled]] at around 5% of the original [[energy]] cost,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Asia-Pacific Partnership on Clean Development and Climate]]|url=http://asiapacificpartnership.org/english/tf_aluminium.aspx|title=Action Plan, page 5, table 2: 4.2 vs. 0.19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406032451/http://www.asiapacificpartnership.org/english/tf_aluminium.aspx|archivedate=2009-04-06|access-date=2009-04-24}}</ref> although many aluminium laminates are not recycled due to difficulties in separating the components and low yield of aluminium metal.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Aluminium}}\n* [[Tin foil hat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Aluminium foil}}\n* [http://www.alufoil.org European Aluminium Foil Association]\n* [http://www.aluminum.org Aluminium Association (USA)]\n* [http://www.madehow.com/Volume-1/Aluminum-Foil.html Aluminium Foil] from ''How Products Are Made,'' vol. 1, Thomson Gale (2005).\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f4OTj9yNOak How It's Made: Aluminium Foil] - HowItsMadeEpisodes channel on YouTube.\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Chemistry}}\n\n[[Category:Cooking utensils]]\n[[Category:Aluminium]]\n[[Category:Packaging materials]]\n[[Category:Metalworking]]\n[[Category:Swiss inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|aluminium foil|other types of foil|Foil (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n<!-- Please DO NOT unnecessarily change Aluminium to Aluminum. For more information, see [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style#National varieties of English]]-->\n[[File:Aluminium cooking foil.jpg|thumb|200px|A sheet of aluminium foil]]\n'''Aluminium foil''' (or '''aluminum foil''' in North America) (often erroneously called '''[[tin foil]]''') is [[aluminium]] prepared in thin [[metal leaf|metal leaves]] with a thickness less than {{convert|0.2|mm|mil|abbr=on}}; thinner gauges down to {{convert|6|micrometre|mil}} are also commonly used.<ref name=\"EAFA facts1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.alufoil.org/facts.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325000221/http://www.alufoil.org/facts.html |archivedate=2016-03-25 }}</ref> In the United States, foils are commonly gauged in thousandths of an inch or [[Thousandth of an inch|mils]]. Standard household foil is typically {{convert|0.016|mm|mil|abbr=on}} thick, and heavy duty household foil is typically {{convert|0.024|mm|mil|abbr=on}}. The [[Foil (metal)|foil]] is pliable, and can be readily bent or wrapped around objects. Thin foils are fragile and are sometimes [[laminate]]d to other materials such as [[plastic]]s or [[paper]] to make them more useful. Aluminium foil supplanted [[tin foil]] in the mid 20th century.\n\nAnnual production of aluminium foil was approximately {{convert|800,000|tonne}} in Europe<ref name=\"EAFA facts1\"/> and {{convert|600,000|tonne}} in the U.S. in 2003.<ref name=aausa>[http://www.aluminum.org/Content/ContentGroups/Tech_Q_and_A/New_Aluminum_Foil_Manual_Covers_It_All.htm Aluminum Association (USA)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227184227/http://www.aluminum.org/Content/ContentGroups/Tech_Q_and_A/New_Aluminum_Foil_Manual_Covers_It_All.htm |date=2007-12-27 }}</ref> Approximately 75% of aluminium foil is used for [[packaging]] of [[food]]s, [[cosmetics]], and chemical products, and 25% is used for industrial applications (e.g., thermal insulation, cables, and electronics).<ref name=aausa/> It can be [[Aluminium recycling|recycled]].\n \nIn [[North America]], aluminium foil is known as \"aluminum foil\". It was popularised by [[Reynolds Metals]], the leading manufacturer in North America. In the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]] it is, informally, widely called tin foil, for historical reasons (similar to how [[steel can]]s are often still called \"[[tin can]]s\"). [[Metallised film]]s are sometimes mistaken for aluminium foil, but are actually polymer films [[thin-film deposition|coated]] with a thin layer of aluminium. In [[Australia]], aluminium foil is widely called alfoil.\n\n== History ==\n\n===Before aluminium foil===\nFoil made from a thin leaf of [[tin]] was commercially available before its aluminium counterpart. [[Tin foil]] was marketed commercially from the late nineteenth into the early twentieth century.  The term \"tin foil\" survives in the English language as a term for the newer aluminium foil. Tin foil is less [[ductility|malleable]] than aluminium foil and tends to give a slight tin taste to food wrapped in it.  Tin foil has been supplanted by aluminium and other materials for wrapping food.<ref>{{cite web |last=Berger |first=Kenneth R. |title=A Brief History of Packaging |url=http://ufdc.ufl.edu/IR00001524/00001 |publisher=University of Florida |accessdate=24 September 2014 |date=December 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909204256/http://ufdc.ufl.edu/IR00001524/00001 |archivedate=9 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe first audio recordings on [[phonograph cylinders]] were made on tin foil.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tinfoil Recordings |url=http://cylinders.library.ucsb.edu/history-tinfoil.php |work=Cylinder Recordings: A Primer |publisher=University of California at Santa Barbara |accessdate=17 October 2011 |author=Cylinder Preservation and Digitization Project, UCSB |format=web page |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016155323/http://cylinders.library.ucsb.edu/history-tinfoil.php |archivedate=16 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===The first aluminium foil===\nTin was first replaced by aluminium in 1910, when the first aluminium foil rolling plant, \"Dr. Lauber, Neher & Cie.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Mary Bellis |url=http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/blaluminum.htm |title=Charles Martin Hall - The History of Aluminum |publisher=Inventors.about.com |date=2012-04-09 |accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref> was opened in [[Kreuzlingen|Emmishofen]], [[Switzerland]]. The plant, owned by J.G. Neher & Sons, the aluminium manufacturers, started in 1886 in [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland, at the foot of the [[Rhine Falls]], capturing the falls' energy to process aluminium. Neher's sons, together with Dr. Lauber, discovered the endless rolling process and the use of aluminium foil as a protective barrier in December 1907.\n\nIn 1911, Bern-based Tobler began wrapping its chocolate bars in aluminium foil, including the unique [[Triangular prism|triangular]] chocolate bar, [[Toblerone]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.alufoil.org/history.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512075406/http://www.alufoil.org/history.html|archivedate=2015-05-12}}</ref> By 1912, aluminium foil was being used by [[Maggi]] (today a Nestl\u00e9 brand) to pack soups and stock cubes.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} \n\nThe first use of foil in the United States was in 1913 for wrapping [[Life Savers]], candy bars, and gum.<ref name=\"Hanlon\">Hanlon, J. (1992). 1st ed. Handbook of Package Engineering, Lancaster, Pennsylvania, and Technomic Publishing: {{ISBN|0-87762-924-2}}. Chapter 3 Films and Foils.</ref> Processes evolved over time to include the use of print, colour, lacquer, laminate and the [[Embossing (manufacturing)|embossing]] of the aluminium.\n\n== Manufacture ==\n[[File:Aluminium foil micrometer.jpg|thumb|250px|A roll of aluminium foil, with [[micrometer]] showing a thickness of {{convert|13|\u00b5m|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}]]\n{{see also|Rolling (metalworking)}}\n\nAluminium foil is produced by rolling sheet [[ingots]] cast from molten [[Aluminium#Production and refinement|billet aluminium]], then re-rolling on sheet and foil rolling mills to the desired thickness, or by continuously casting and cold rolling. To maintain a constant thickness in aluminium foil production, [[beta radiation]] is passed through the foil to a sensor on the other side. If the intensity becomes too high, then the rollers adjust, increasing the thickness. If the intensities become too low and the foil has become too thick, the rollers apply more pressure, causing the foil to be made thinner.\n\nThe continuous casting method is much less energy intensive and has become the preferred process.<ref name=\"Robertson\">Robertson, G. (2006). 2nd ed. Food Packaging, Principles and Practise, Boca Raton, FL, Taylor & Francis Group: {{ISBN|0-8493-3775-5}}. Chapter 7 Metal Packaging Materials.</ref> For thicknesses below {{convert|0.025|mm|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}, two layers are usually put together for the final pass and afterwards separated which produces foil with one bright side and one matte side.<ref name=degarmo/> The two sides in contact with each other are matte and the exterior sides become bright; this is done to reduce tearing, increase production rates, control thickness, and get around the need for a smaller diameter roller.<ref name=degarmo>{{Cite book | last = Degarmo | first = E. Paul | last2 = Black | first2 = J T. | last3 = Kohser | first3 = Ronald A. | title = Materials and Processes in Manufacturing | publisher = Wiley | page = 386 | year = 2003 | edition = 9th | isbn = 0-471-65653-4}}</ref>\n\nSome [[lubrication]] is needed during the rolling stages; otherwise, the foil surface can become marked with a [[herringbone pattern]]. These lubricants are sprayed on the foil surface before passing through the mill rolls. [[Kerosene]] based lubricants are commonly used, although oils approved for food contact must be used for foil intended for food packaging.\n\nAluminium becomes work hardened during the cold rolling process and is [[annealing (metallurgy)|annealed]] for most purposes. The rolls of foil are heated until the degree of softness is reached, which may be up to {{convert|340|C}} for 12 hours. During this heating, the lubricating oils are burned off, leaving a dry surface. Lubricant oils may not be completely burnt off for hard temper rolls, which can make subsequent coating or printing more difficult.\n\nThe rolls of aluminium foil are then slit on [[slitter|slitter rewinding]] machines into smaller rolls. Roll slitting and rewinding is an essential part of the finishing process.\n\n== Properties ==\n[[File:Rubber with sodium silicate beads 6 alu backside.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[photomicrograph|Microscopic close-up]] of aluminium foil on the back of an [[intumescent]] rubber strip.]]\n\nAluminium foils thicker than {{convert|25|\u00b5m|mil|lk=out|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} are impermeable to oxygen and water. Foils thinner than this become slightly permeable due to minute pinholes caused by the production process.\n\nAluminium foil has a shiny side and a matte side. The shiny side is produced when the aluminium is rolled during the final pass. It is difficult to produce rollers with a gap fine enough to cope with the foil gauge, therefore, for the final pass, two sheets are rolled at the same time, doubling the thickness of the gauge at entry to the rollers. When the sheets are later separated, the inside surface is dull, and the outside surface is shiny. This difference in the finish has led to the perception that favouring a side has an effect when cooking. While many believe (wrongly) that the different properties keep heat out when wrapped with the shiny finish facing out, and keep heat in with the shiny finish facing inwards, the actual difference is imperceptible without instrumentation. Increased reflectivity decreases both absorption and [[Black-body_radiation|emission]] of radiation. Foil may have a non-stick coating on only one side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reynoldskitchens.com/media/10246730/reynolds_wrap_faq.pdf |title=Frequently Asked Questions |accessdate=2014-08-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021084635/http://www.reynoldskitchens.com/media/10246730/reynolds_wrap_faq.pdf |archivedate=2014-10-21 }}</ref> The [[reflectivity]] of bright aluminium foil is 88% while dull embossed foil is about 80%.<ref name=\"Hanlon\"/>\n\n==Uses==\n\n=== Packaging ===\n[[File:Reese's peanut butter cups.jpg|thumb|250px|Chocolates in aluminium foil packaging]]\n\nAluminium is used for packaging as it is highly malleable: it can be easily converted to thin sheets and folded, rolled or packed. Aluminium foil acts as a total barrier to light and oxygen (which cause fats to oxidise or become rancid), odours and flavours, moistness, and germs, and so it is used broadly in food and pharmaceutical packaging, including long-life packs ([[aseptic processing|aseptic packaging]]) for drinks and dairy goods, which allows storing without refrigeration. Aluminium foil containers and trays are used to bake pies and to pack [[Take-out|takeaway]] meals, ready snacks and long life [[pet]] foods.\n\nAluminium foil is widely sold into the [[consumer]] market, often in rolls of {{convert|500|mm|abbr=on}} width and several metres in length.<ref>[http://www.reynoldspkg.com/reynoldskitchens/en/product_category.asp?cat_id=1337 Examples of products]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218165509/http://www.reynoldspkg.com/reynoldskitchens/en/product_category.asp?cat_id=1337 |date=2008-12-18 }}</ref> It is used for wrapping food in order to preserve it, for example, when storing leftover food in a [[refrigerator]] (where it serves the additional purpose of preventing odour exchange), when taking [[sandwich]]es on a journey, when baking, or when selling some kinds of [[take-away]] or [[fast food]]. [[Tex-Mex]] restaurants in the [[United States]], for example, typically provide take-away [[burrito]]s wrapped in aluminium foil.\n\n=== Insulation ===\nAluminium foil is widely used for radiation shield (barrier and reflectivity), heat exchangers ([[heat conduction]]) and cable liners (barrier and [[electrical conductivity]]). Aluminium foil's heat conductive qualities make it a common accessory in [[hookah]] smoking: a sheet of perforated aluminium foil is frequently placed between the coal and the tobacco, allowing the tobacco to be heated without coming into direct contact with the burning coal.\n\n=== Electromagnetic shielding ===\nThe [[Electromagnetic shielding|shielding effectiveness]] of aluminium foil depends upon the type of incident field (electric, magnetic, or plane wave), the thickness of the foil, and the frequency (which determines the [[skin depth]]). Shielding effectiveness is usually broken down into a reflection loss (the energy bounces off the shield rather than penetrates it) and an absorption loss (the energy is dissipated within the shield).\n\nAlthough aluminium is non-magnetic, it is a good conductor, so even a thin sheet reflects almost all of an incident electric wave. At frequencies more than 100&nbsp;MHz, the ''transmitted'' electric field is attenuated by more than 80 [[decibel]]s (dB) (less than 10<sup>\u22128</sup> = 0.00000001 of the power gets through) <ref>{{Citation |last=Ott |first=Henry |title=Noise Reduction Techniques in Electronic Systems |year=1976 |publisher=Wiley Interscience |isbn=0-471-65726-3 |doi= }}. {{Harvtxt|Ott|1976|loc=figure 6-13}} graphs reflection loss for copper, and shows electric field and plane wave losses at greater than 90&nbsp;dB.</ref> -- however actual energy absorption is minimal:  the remaining high-frequency rf energy is almost perfectly reflected from uniform flat aluminium surface, and thus, reflected signal may continue to propagate internally, and if holes or passages of suitable geometry exist in the shield, signal propagation may continue out through those, the aluminium being good material for implementation of a microwave-frequency [[waveguide]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nThin sheets of aluminium are not very effective at attenuating low-frequency magnetic fields.  The shielding effectiveness is dependent upon the skin depth. A field travelling through one skin depth will lose about 63 per cent of its energy (it is attenuated to 1/e = 1/2.718... of its original energy).  Thin shields also have internal reflections that reduce the shielding effectiveness.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ott|1976|pp=155&ndash;156}}</ref>  For effective shielding from a magnetic field, the shield should be several skin depths thick.  Aluminium foil is about {{convert|1|mil|um}}; a thickness of {{convert|10|mil|um}} (ten times thicker) offers less than 1&nbsp;dB of shielding at 1&nbsp;kHz, about 8&nbsp;dB at 10&nbsp;kHz, and about 25&nbsp;dB at 100&nbsp;kHz.  At these frequencies a [[Ferromagnetism|ferromagnetic material]] such as [[mild steel]] is much more effective, due to different and complementary [[Permeability_(electromagnetism)|electromagnetic permeability]] properties, and common practical shielding implementations utilise both an inner high-frequency reflective material such as aluminium, preferably bonded (via [[Annealing (metallurgy)|annealing]] or [[electroplating]], done to avoid capacitance between separated layers), to a more substantial structural ferromagnetic shell, usually mild steel (in specialized applications, more expensive, less structurally useful and less workable materials may be preferred.)  Despite the relative low mass density of aluminium, this design is usually both lighter and more effective than an equivalently absorptive design utilizing aluminium alone (although with poorer heat dissipative properties, typically accommodated by improved ventilation, which itself needs careful consideration in order to preserve the desired shielding effectiveness).{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n=== Cooking ===\nAluminium foil is also used for [[barbecue|barbecuing]] delicate foods,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zXm8ccnB0P8C&pg=PA207&dq=Aluminium+foil+is+used+for+barbecuing+delicate+foods&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjkLH6r9nUAhUI6mMKHdTmBmEQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=Aluminium%20foil%20is%20used%20for%20barbecuing%20delicate%20foods&f=false|title=Kitchen on Fire!: Mastering the Art of Cooking in 12 Weeks (or Less)|last=Said|first=Olivier|last2=MikeC|first2=Chef|date=2011-11-22|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=9780738214535|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022234134/https://books.google.com/books?id=zXm8ccnB0P8C&pg=PA207&dq=Aluminium+foil+is+used+for+barbecuing+delicate+foods&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjkLH6r9nUAhUI6mMKHdTmBmEQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=Aluminium%20foil%20is%20used%20for%20barbecuing%20delicate%20foods&f=false|archivedate=2017-10-22}}</ref> such as mushrooms and vegetables. Using this method, sometimes called a '''hobo pack''', food is wrapped in foil, then placed on the grill, preventing loss of moisture that may result in a less appealing texture.\n\nAs is the case with all metallic items, aluminium foil reacts to being placed in a [[microwave oven]]. This is because of the [[electromagnetic field]]s of the microwaves inducing electric currents in the foil and high [[voltage|potentials]] at the sharp points of the foil sheet; if the potential is sufficiently high, it will cause [[electric arc]]ing to areas with lower potential, even to the air surrounding the sheet.  Modern microwave ovens have been designed to prevent damage to the [[cavity magnetron]] tube from microwave energy reflection, and aluminium packages designed for microwave heating are available.<ref>Huss, G. (1997) Microwaveable Packaging and Dual-Ovenable Materials in The Wiley Encyclopedia of Packaging Technology, 2nd ed., edited by Brody, A. and Marsch, K. New York, John Wiley and Sons</ref>\n\n=== Art and decoration ===\nHeavier foils made of aluminium are used for art, decoration, and crafts, especially in bright metallic colours. Metallic aluminium, normally silvery in colour, can be made to take on other colours through [[anodization|anodisation]]. Anodising creates an oxide layer on the aluminium surface that can accept coloured dyes or metallic salts, depending on the process used. In this way, aluminium is used to create an inexpensive gold foil that actually contains no gold, and many other bright metallic colours. These foils are sometimes used in distinctive packaging.\n\n=== Geochemical sampling ===\nFoil is used by organic/petroleum geochemists for protecting rock samples taken from the fields and in the labs where the sample is subject to [[biomarker]] analysis. While plastic or cloth bags are normally used for a geological sampling exercise, cloth bags are permeable and may allow organic solvents or oils (such as oils imparted from the skin) to taint the sample, and traces of the plastics from plastic bags may also taint the sample. Foil provides a seal to the ingress of organic solvents and does not taint the sample. Foil is also used extensively in geochemical laboratories to provide a barrier for the geochemist, and for sample storage.\n\n=== Ribbon microphones ===\nThe material used in many [[ribbon microphone]]s is aluminium leaf, or \"[[Metal leaf|imitation silver leaf]]\", as it is sometimes called. This is pure aluminium and is around 0.6 to 2.0 micrometres thick. It is virtually the same material that the BBC used on [[Coles 4038|Coles ribbon]]s, with the exception that they also hand beat the leaf even thinner. They did this by sandwiching the ribbon between toilet paper and beating with a [[ball-peen hammer]]. This \"cold forges\" the leaf. The aluminium leaf was then annealed for an hour in an oven to restore flexibility. Corrugations must also be imparted into the ribbon: Coles used 25 per inch (1&nbsp;mm cycle). RCA 44BX has 19 corrugations per inch (0.7&nbsp;mm cycle) and is around {{convert|50|mm|abbr=on}} long; RCA 77 has 13 corrugations per inch (0.5&nbsp;mm cycle). RCA ribbon material is around 1 to 1.5 micrometres (0.00005&nbsp;inch) thick. The new Nady ribbon plus AEA both state that they use 2 micrometre aluminium ribbon in their microphones.{{Vague|date=March 2013}}\n\n== Environmental issues ==\n{{See also|Aluminium recycling}}\n\nSome aluminium foil products can be [[recycling|recycled]] at around 5% of the original [[energy]] cost,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Asia-Pacific Partnership on Clean Development and Climate]]|url=http://asiapacificpartnership.org/english/tf_aluminium.aspx|title=Action Plan, page 5, table 2: 4.2 vs. 0.19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406032451/http://www.asiapacificpartnership.org/english/tf_aluminium.aspx|archivedate=2009-04-06|access-date=2009-04-24}}</ref> although many aluminium laminates are not recycled due to difficulties in separating the components and low yield of aluminium metal.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Aluminium}}\n* [[Tin foil hat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Aluminium foil}}\n* [http://www.alufoil.org European Aluminium Foil Association]\n* [http://www.aluminum.org Aluminium Association (USA)]\n* [http://www.madehow.com/Volume-1/Aluminum-Foil.html Aluminium Foil] from ''How Products Are Made,'' vol. 1, Thomson Gale (2005).\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f4OTj9yNOak How It's Made: Aluminium Foil] - HowItsMadeEpisodes channel on YouTube.\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Chemistry}}\n\n[[Category:Cooking utensils]]\n[[Category:Aluminium]]\n[[Category:Packaging materials]]\n[[Category:Metalworking]]\n[[Category:Swiss inventions]]\n", "name_user": "Wiki13565", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 941654983 by108.44.250.213(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aluminium_foil"}
{"title_page": "Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest", "text_new": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Morocco\n| Member station = [[SNRT]]\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal Selection\n | 1980\n}}\n| ESC apps = 1\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC last = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC best = 18th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC worst = 18th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| Website = \n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/morocco\n| Current = 1980\n}}\n\n[[Morocco]] entered the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] for the first, and so far only, time at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980]] with the song \"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\", performed by [[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]] in the [[Arabic language]].\n\n==Contest history==\nMorocco debuted at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980]], held in [[The Hague]], Netherlands,<ref name=\"32years\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/32-years-ago-today-morocco-s-only-ever-participation|title=32 years ago today- Morocco's only ever participation|date=19 April 2012|publisher=[[European Broacasting Union]]|website=Eurovision.tv|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> becoming the first African and Arab country to enter the contest. The entry was organized by Moroccan broadcaster, [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision (SNRT)]].\n\nTheir song for the contest was \"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\", performed by Moroccan singer [[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]]. The song received 7 points, all from [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest|Italy]], and placed 18th, ahead of [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Finland]].<ref name=\"32years\"/>\n\nAfter their poor placing in the contest, SNRT announced that they would not return for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1981|1981 contest]] qith [[Hassan II of Morocco|King Hassan II]] issuing a Royal Statement stating.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Future==\nA second Moroccan broadcaster, [[2M TV]], has expressed their intention to join the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU). Should their application be successful, 2M TV, Morocco would be eligible to return to the contest with an alternative broadcaster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=398|title=2MTV aims to full EBU membership|date=12 July 2007|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=17 October 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120195318/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=398|archivedate=20 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/8972|title=Morocco to return in the next few years?|last=Kuipers|first=Michael|date=12 July 2007|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=5 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=4003|title=Commercial channel interested to join Eurovision Song Contest|date=31 August 2008|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=6 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906193756/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=4003|archivedate=6 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Akhasvil|first1=Sopon|title=With the IBA in peril, Israel may withdraw in 2015|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2014/06/03/israel-withdraw-2015/52317/|website=Wiwibloggs.com|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=4 June 2014|date=3 June 2014}}</ref> In May 2018, the Israeli Minister of Communications announced that he would invite countries of the [[Arab world]] to participate in the {{Escyr|2019}} contest in [[Tel Aviv]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://escxtra.com/2018/05/22/israeli-arabic-tunisia-eurovision/|title=Israeli Minister \u201cto invite\u201d Arabic nations, including Tunisia, to take part in Eurovision 2019|date=22 May 2018|accessdate=2 December 2019|website=escxtra.com|first=Ryan|last=Cobb}}</ref> but Morocco was not on the list of participating countries released on 7 November 2018.\n\n== Contestants ==\n<!-- ;Table key\n{{legend|#FFCC33|Winner}}\n{{legend|#CCCCCC|Second place}}\n{{legend|#cc9966|Third place}}\n{{legend|#FE8080|Last place}} -->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!width=50px|Final\n!width=50px|Points\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1980}}\n|[[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]]\n|[[Arabic]]\n|\"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\" {{small|(\u0628\u0637\u0627\u0642\u0629 \u062d\u0628)}}\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|7\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate from {{Escyr|1981}} to {{Escyr|2020}}}}\n|}\n\n== Conductors ==\n* {{flagicon|France}} {{flagicon|Algeria}} Jean Claudric 1980 (finished 18th)<ref>[http://www.eurovisionartists.nl/conductor/dir020.asp?ID=58 And the conductor is... Jean Claudric]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eurovisioncovers.co.uk/xtmor.htm Points to and from Morocco] ''eurovisioncovers.co.uk''\n\n{{Morocco in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Morocco\n| Member station = [[SNRT]]\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal Selection\n | 1980\n}}\n| ESC apps = 1\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC last = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC best = 18th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| ESC worst = 18th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]]\n| Website = \n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/morocco\n| Current = 1980\n}}\n\n[[Morocco]] entered the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] for the first, and so far only, time at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980]] with the song \"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\", performed by [[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]] in the [[Arabic language]].\n\n==Contest history==\nMorocco debuted at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980]], held in [[The Hague]], Netherlands,<ref name=\"32years\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/32-years-ago-today-morocco-s-only-ever-participation|title=32 years ago today- Morocco's only ever participation|date=19 April 2012|publisher=[[European Broacasting Union]]|website=Eurovision.tv|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> becoming the first African and Arab country to enter the contest. The entry was organized by Moroccan broadcaster, [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision (SNRT)]].\n\nTheir song for the contest was \"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\", performed by Moroccan singer [[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]]. The song received 7 points, all from [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest|Italy]], and placed 18th, ahead of [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Finland]].<ref name=\"32years\">\n\nAfter their poor placing in the contest, SNRT announced that they would not return for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1981|1981 contest]] qith [[Hassan II of Morocco|King Hassan II]] issuing a Royal Statement stating.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Future==\nA second Moroccan broadcaster, [[2M TV]], has expressed their intention to join the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU). Should their application be successful, 2M TV, Morocco would be eligible to return to the contest with an alternative broadcaster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=398|title=2MTV aims to full EBU membership|date=12 July 2007|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=17 October 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120195318/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=398|archivedate=20 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/8972|title=Morocco to return in the next few years?|last=Kuipers|first=Michael|date=12 July 2007|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=5 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=4003|title=Commercial channel interested to join Eurovision Song Contest|date=31 August 2008|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=6 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906193756/http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=4003|archivedate=6 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Akhasvil|first1=Sopon|title=With the IBA in peril, Israel may withdraw in 2015|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2014/06/03/israel-withdraw-2015/52317/|website=Wiwibloggs.com|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=4 June 2014|date=3 June 2014}}</ref> In May 2018, the Israeli Minister of Communications announced that he would invite countries of the [[Arab world]] to participate in the {{Escyr|2019}} contest in [[Tel Aviv]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://escxtra.com/2018/05/22/israeli-arabic-tunisia-eurovision/|title=Israeli Minister \u201cto invite\u201d Arabic nations, including Tunisia, to take part in Eurovision 2019|date=22 May 2018|accessdate=2 December 2019|website=escxtra.com|first=Ryan|last=Cobb}}</ref> but Morocco was not on the list of participating countries released on 7 November 2018.\n\n== Contestants ==\n<!-- ;Table key\n{{legend|#FFCC33|Winner}}\n{{legend|#CCCCCC|Second place}}\n{{legend|#cc9966|Third place}}\n{{legend|#FE8080|Last place}} -->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!width=50px|Final\n!width=50px|Points\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1980}}\n|[[Samira Said|Samira Bensa\u00efd]]\n|[[Arabic]]\n|\"[[Bitaqat Hub]]\" {{small|(\u0628\u0637\u0627\u0642\u0629 \u062d\u0628)}}\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|7\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate from {{Escyr|1981}} to {{Escyr|2020}}}}\n|}\n\n== Conductors ==\n* {{flagicon|France}} {{flagicon|Algeria}} Jean Claudric 1980 (finished 18th)<ref>[http://www.eurovisionartists.nl/conductor/dir020.asp?ID=58 And the conductor is... Jean Claudric]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eurovisioncovers.co.uk/xtmor.htm Points to and from Morocco] ''eurovisioncovers.co.uk''\n\n{{Morocco in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n", "name_user": "Grk1011", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContest history:missing slash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morocco_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Ontario}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case      = [[Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre|Sunnybrook Hospital]], [[Toronto]]\n| confirmed_cases = 3,255<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/>\n| deaths          = 67<ref name=\"Ontario_official\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus |title=The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |website=ontario.ca |access-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228004601/https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus |archive-date=February 28, 2020 }}</ref>, 81 ([https://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/coronavirustracker/]), 92 ([[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario#Geographical distribution|PC]]) or 98 ([https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/03/health-officials-in-peel-region-accidentally-mail-wrong-covid-19-test-results-ontario-to-reveal-projection-numbers-today-stars-count-says-ontario-has-3210-cases-92-deaths.html])\n| recovery_cases  = 1,023<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/>\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date    = January 25, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| location        = [[Ontario]], Canada\n| website         = [https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus Ontario Government]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario''' is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a [[novel virus|novel]] infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|COVID-19 in Canada]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 worldwide pandemic]] occurred in the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Ontario]], and was confirmed on January 27, 2020, after a man returned to [[Toronto]] from travel in [[China]], including [[Wuhan]]. As of April 2 at 4&nbsp;p.m. ET,<!-- Updated by Government of Ontario every morning at 10:30 and afternoon at 5:30 --> there have been 3,255 confirmed cases, 1,023 recoveries, and 67 deaths.<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-new-covid-19-cases-total-sunday-1.5498410|title=Ontario confirms 39 new COVID-19 cases, bringing provincial total to 142|date=March 15, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"death\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-covid-19-ontario-tuesday-1.5500006 |title=1st death confirmed in Ontario as province declares state of emergency over COVID-19 &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref> Overall 57,874 people have been tested for the virus, with 60,681 people (95.6%) testing negative and 2,793 people (4.4%) testing positive,<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/> the remaining people are still waiting on their test results due to a backlog in testing.<ref name=\"starbacklog\"/><ref name=\"urlConcerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario | CBC News\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-19-coronavirus-ontario-testing-delays-wait-time-1.5502605 |title=Concerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320161216/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-19-coronavirus-ontario-testing-delays-wait-time-1.5502605 |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of April 3, of all cases 381 have been hospitalized and 116 required intensive care.<ref name=\"Report-2020-03-29\">{{cite web |url=https://files.ontario.ca/moh-covid-19-report-en-2020-03-31.pdf |title=files.ontario.ca |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Government of Ontario declared a state of emergency,<ref name=\"emergency\">{{cite news |last1=Rodrigues |first1=Gabby |title=Ontario government declares state of emergency amid coronavirus pandemic |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6688074/ontario-doug-ford-coronavirus-covid-19-march-17/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Global News |agency=Corus Entertainment |date=March 17, 2020 |language=en-CA}}</ref> closing bars and restaurants (with the exception of take-out and delivery services), as well as libraries, theatres, cinemas, schools and daycares and all public gatherings of more than 50 people (later reduced to 5 people on March 28).<ref name=\"death\"/><ref name=\"gatheringban5\">{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6746181/ontario-ban-gatherings/|title=Ontario government bans gatherings of 5 or more people in bid to stop coronavirus spread|website=Global News|access-date=28 March 2020|date=28 March 2020|last1=Rocca|first1=Ryan|last2=Shah|first2=Maryam|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, the government announced on March 17 that Ontario had \"some evidence of community transmission\" of COVID-19.<ref name=\"urlToronto waking up to new reality amid evidence of COVID-19 community spread | CBC News\">{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-waking-up-to-new-reality-amid-evidence-of-covid-19-community-spread-1.5499768| title=Toronto waking up to new reality amid 'evidence' of COVID-19 community spread by prof. Doctor Aman ALBARGHOUTI| first=Lauren| last=Pelley| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200320015455/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-waking-up-to-new-reality-amid-evidence-of-covid-19-community-spread-1.5499768| archive-date=March 20, 2020| date=March 17, 2020| accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3rd, the Ontario government released projections indicating 3 000 to 15 000 deaths were possible unless further measures were taken. The same models indicated that had no mitigation measures been undertaken, the death toll could have reached 100 000.<ref>https://www.cp24.com/news/3-000-to-15-000-could-die-in-ontario-due-to-covid-19-provincial-modelling-1.4880754</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Canada/Ontario medical cases chart}}\n\n===January\u2013February===\nOn January 23, the first presumptive case in Canada was admitted to [[Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre]] in [[Toronto]] and placed into a negative pressure chamber.<ref name=\"RC\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/01/ontario-confirms-first-case-of-wuhan-novel-coronavirus.html|title=Ontario Confirms First Case of Wuhan Novel Coronavirus|date=January 25, 2020|work=|accessdate=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129194142/https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1496143/coronavirus-confirmation-2e-cas-toronto|archive-date=29 January 2020|publisher=Government of Ontario|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/tracking-every-case-of-covid-19-in-canada-1.4852102|title=Tracking every case of COVID-19 in Canada|date=2020-03-13|website=Coronavirus|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315124205/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/tracking-every-case-of-covid-19-in-canada-1.4852102|archive-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The patient, a male in his 50s who travelled between Wuhan and [[Guangzhou]] before returning to Toronto on January 22, contacted emergency services following rapid onset symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6462626/coronavirus-toronto-hospital/|title=Health officials to announce 'presumptive case' of coronavirus in Toronto|website=Global News|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125222207/https://globalnews.ca/news/6462626/coronavirus-toronto-hospital/|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The presumption of infection in the patient was made after a rapid test was done at [[Public Health Ontario]]'s Toronto laboratory. Final testing conducted at the [[National Microbiology Laboratory]] in Winnipeg, [[Manitoba]] confirmed the presumptive case on January 25.<ref name=\"RC\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Authorities said that the patient was experiencing respiratory problems but was in stable condition.<ref name=\"RC\"/> His condition later improved and he was released from hospital on January 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|title=Canada's 1st coronavirus patient discharged from Toronto hospital|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131165249/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, the Chief Medical Officer of Health of [[Ontario]] announced the man's wife as the second presumptive case.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=2nd presumptive case of coronavirus confirmed in Ontario|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-wuhan-ontario-second-case-1.5441401|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=27 January 2020|date=27 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127133636/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-wuhan-ontario-second-case-1.5441401|archive-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials reported that she was in good condition and that she was asymptomatic.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn January 31, the third case in [[Ontario]] (and the fourth case in Canada) was reported in the city of [[London, Ontario|London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6489956/3rd-case-coronavirus-confirmed-ontario/|title=Woman in her 20s confirmed as 3rd case of coronavirus in Ontario|website=Global News|access-date=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|last1=Patton|first1=Jessica|last2=Dhanraj|first2=Travis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201045003/https://globalnews.ca/news/6489956/3rd-case-coronavirus-confirmed-ontario/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials said that the individual, a woman in her 20s and a student at [[University of Western Ontario]], returned from Wuhan on January 23.<ref name=\"CBC2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|title=Ontario confirms 3rd coronavirus patient, Toronto hospital discharges the 1st one|last=Boisvert|first=Nick|publisher=CBC News|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=31 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131165249/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She was [[asymptomatic]] and had tested negative at first, but additional advanced testing confirmed that the woman had low levels of the virus in her system.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/> Officials said that the individual wore a mask during her voyage and she voluntarily entered self-isolation upon her return, making a full recovery after two or three days.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/> On the same day, the [[Government of Ontario]] reported that 17 cases were under investigation within its provincial jurisdiction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov|title=The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|website=Government of Ontario|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131014611/https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials said that most of the individuals under investigation were awaiting results while in self-isolation at home.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-ontario-toronto-update-public-health-1.5445620|title=No new cases of coronavirus in Ontario, public health officials say|publisher=CBC News|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130152659/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-ontario-toronto-update-public-health-1.5445620|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 30, the associate medical officer of Ontario said that the province had conducted a total of 67 tests with 38 negative results.<ref name=\"CBC\"/> Officials said that all possible cases\u2014including previous negative results\u2014were being retested as additional assessments become available.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/>\n\n[[CFB Trenton]] in [[Trenton, Ontario]] has been used as a quarantine facility for repatriated Canadians since February 7.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/happy-to-be-back-flight-carrying-canadians-from-wuhan-lands-in-ontario-1.4801361|title= 'Happy to be back': Flight carrying Canadians from Wuhan lands in Ontario|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=7 February 2020}}</ref> As of March 20, 12 positive cases for the virus of the repatriated citizens at CFB Trenton have been reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/victoria-grand-princess-passenger-says-12-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-quarantine-1.4862142|title=Victoria Grand Princess passenger says 12 diagnosed with COVID-19 in quarantine|publisher=vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320231507/https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/victoria-grand-princess-passenger-says-12-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-quarantine-1.4862142|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, a fourth presumptive case in Ontario was announced of a woman in her 20s who presented to a hospital on February 21 with symptoms after travelling to Wuhan. The woman was tested locally with a positive test result and the sample was sent to the [[National Microbiology Laboratory]] in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=\"20200224urlHealthofficials_CBCNews\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-update-1.5473473 |title=Health officials say system to manage coronavirus is 'working quite well' amid 4th case in Ontario &#124; CBC News |accessdate=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201033/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-update-1.5473473 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 24, health officials in Ontario stated that all three previous cases in Ontario were \"resolved\", which means patients had two consecutive negative test results 24 hours apart and that the \"system was working\".<ref name=\"20200224urlHealthofficials_CBCNews\"/>\n\n===March===\n[[File:Leslie street on a Thursday morning during the COVID-19 pandemic - 1.jpg|thumb|[[Leslie Street]] empty at 9:00 a.m. on a weekday in Toronto.]]\n[[File:YRTReducedScheduleNotice.jpg|thumb|[[York Region Transit]] bus schedule reduction in March]]\nOn March 5, Ontario reported three more cases of the virus, for a total of 23 in the province, with cases in [[Toronto]], [[Kitchener, ON|Kitchener]], and [[Mississauga, ON|Mississauga]] being reported. The three cases came from [[Iran]], [[Italy]], and the [[Grand Princess|''Grand Princess'' cruise ship]], respectively. It was also announced that another case in Ontario was resolved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-confirms-3-new-cases-coronavirus-1.5486670|title=Ontario confirms 3 new cases of coronavirus, bringing total to 23 in province|date=5 March 2020|website=Toronto|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221134501/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-confirms-3-new-cases-coronavirus-1.5486670|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFive cases, two imported from each of Iran and the ''Grand Princess'', and one from Las Vegas, were reported on March 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6640864/ontario-new-coronavirus-cases/|title=Officials announce new cases of COVID-19 in Ontario for total of 28|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135041/https://globalnews.ca/news/6640864/ontario-new-coronavirus-cases/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Four more cases were reported to have been imported from Colorado, [[Washington, D.C.]], France, and Germany on March 8, bringing the total to 32.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6647308/ontario-coronavirus-woman-travelled-colorado/|title=Ontario reports additional case of COVID-19, woman who travelled to Colorado|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309135022/https://globalnews.ca/news/6647308/ontario-coronavirus-woman-travelled-colorado/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-reports-two-more-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-the-total-to-31-1.4843941|title=Ontario reports two more cases of COVID-19, bringing the total to 31|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9879814--risk-to-peel-citizens-is-still-low-peel-region-reports-third-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus/ |title='Risk to Peel citizens is still low': Peel Region reports third confirmed case of coronavirus |publisher=Toronto.com |accessdate=2020-03-08 |date=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153828/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9879814--risk-to-peel-citizens-is-still-low-peel-region-reports-third-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Ontario confirmed two new cases of coronavirus, bringing the total number of cases in the province to 34. They are an octogenarian and a septuagenarian from Toronto having travelled to Iran, where cases of COVID-19 had multiplied in recent weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1654787/coronavirus-ontario-32-cas-peel-voyage-allemagne|title=34 cas de coronavirus en Ontario, 4 gu\u00e9risons {{!}} Coronavirus : Ontario|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone Soci\u00e9t\u00e9-|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, a close contact of a previous case and a man who travelled to Switzerland were confirmed as Ontario's 35th and 36th case, respectively. Later the same day, a Sudbury man who attended the [[Prospectors & Developers Association of Canada]] (PDAC) conference in Toronto on March 2\u20133 was confirmed as the 37th positive case, and the first in northern Ontario.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sudbury man who attended Toronto convention confirmed as Ontario's 37th coronavirus case |author=Rodriguez, Gabby |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6655133/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-36-case-switzerland/amp/ |work=Global News |date=2020-03-10 |accessdate=2020-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311164407/https://globalnews.ca/news/6655133/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-36-case-switzerland/amp/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, a 40-year-old man who recently travelled to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]] was confirmed as the first coronavirus case in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 1st case of COVID-19 reported in Ottawa |author=Rocca, Ryan |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6660518/ottawa-first-coronavirus-case/ |work=Global News |date=2020-03-11 |accessdate=2020-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312154951/https://globalnews.ca/news/6660518/ottawa-first-coronavirus-case/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The overall coronavirus case number in Ontario rose to 42 on the same day. On March 12, 17 new cases were confirmed including a baby boy who had recently visited the [[North York General Hospital]] in Toronto. That day, the total number of cases in Ontario increased to 59.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/17-more-cases-of-covid-19-including-a-baby-boy-confirmed-in-ontario-1.4850170| title=17 more cases of COVID-19, including a baby boy, confirmed in Ontario| first=Sean| last=Davidson| date=March 12, 2020| website=ctvnews.ca| access-date=March 12, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313015745/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/17-more-cases-of-covid-19-including-a-baby-boy-confirmed-in-ontario-1.4850170| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On March 13, health officials reported 19 additional cases, bringing the number of cases to 79, and on the 14th, 24 more, making the total 103.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rodrigues|first=Gabby|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6671583/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-cases-march-13/|title=Ontario confirms 19 new cases of coronavirus, bringing provincial total to 79|date=March 13, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134544/https://globalnews.ca/news/6671583/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-cases-march-13/|archive-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> On March 17, it was announced that a man in his 70s, who had died in [[Barrie]], was the first death in Ontario as a result of COVID-19.<ref name=\"death\"/> On March 18, a player for the [[Ottawa Senators]] hockey team was tested positive.<ref name=\"ottsenpositive\">{{cite news |last1=March 18 |first1=Bruce Garrioch Updated: |title=Ottawa Senators player becomes first NHLer to test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-senators-player-tests-positive-covid-19 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Ottawa Citizen |publisher=Postmedia |date=18 March 2020 |language=en-CA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318081809/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-senators-player-tests-positive-covid-19 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 23 new cases were confirmed in Ontario that day, bringing the total number of cases to 212.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/23-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-ontario-bringing-provincial-total-to-212-1.4857982| title=23 new cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Ontario, bringing provincial total to 212| first=Sean| last=Davidson| date=March 18, 2020| website=ctvnews.ca| url-status=live| archive-date=March 18, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173356/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/23-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-ontario-bringing-provincial-total-to-212-1.4857982| access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom the initial case on January 23 to March 18, over half of the reported cases are reported in [[Toronto]] (220 cases),<ref name=\"urlCOVID-19 \u2013 City of Toronto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/home/covid-19/ |title=COVID-19 \u2013 City of Toronto |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321014118/https://www.toronto.ca/home/covid-19/ |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> of which 11 are under investigation for community transmission.<ref name=\"url11 hospitalized as coronavirus cases rise to 128 in Toronto | News\">{{cite web |url=https://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-coronavirus-pandemic-new-cases-hospitilization |title=11 hospitalized as coronavirus cases rise to 128 in Toronto &#124; News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320152521/https://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-coronavirus-pandemic-new-cases-hospitilization |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] reported 23 cases<ref name=\"urlNovel Coronavirus (COVID-19) | City of Hamilton, Ontario, Canada\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hamilton.ca/public-health/covid-19/novel-coronavirus-covid-19 |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) &#124; City of Hamilton, Ontario, Canada |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150745/https://www.hamilton.ca/public-health/covid-19/novel-coronavirus-covid-19 |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Ottawa]] 19 cases,<ref name=\"urlNovel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Ottawa Public Health\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ottawapublichealth.ca/en/public-health-topics/novel-coronavirus.aspx |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Ottawa Public Health |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319013757/https://www.ottawapublichealth.ca/en/public-health-topics/novel-coronavirus.aspx |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham]] reported 18 cases<ref name=\"urlCOVID-19 Update - Region of Durham\">{{cite web |url=https://www.durham.ca/en/health-and-wellness/novel-coronavirus-update.aspx |title=COVID-19 Update - Region of Durham |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320152830/https://www.durham.ca/en/health-and-wellness/novel-coronavirus-update.aspx |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]] reporting 14 cases.<ref name=\"urlConfirmed positive cases in Waterloo Region - Region of Waterloo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/health-and-wellness/confirmed-positive-cases-in-waterloo-region.aspx |title=Confirmed positive cases in Waterloo Region - Region of Waterloo |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150737/https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/health-and-wellness/confirmed-positive-cases-in-waterloo-region.aspx |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn April 2, [[Lakeridge Health]] declared an outbreak of COVID-19 at [[Lakeridge Health Oshawa]] in [[Oshawa, Ontario|Oshawa]], and announced that one of its in-patient units would be temporarily closed after a hospital-acquired case of COVID-19 was transmitted to a health care worker treating the patient.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freeman |first1=Joshua |title=Lakeridge Health declares COVID-19 outbreak at Oshawa Hospital |url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/lakeridge-health-declares-covid-19-outbreak-at-oshawa-hospital-1.4880155 |website=CTV News |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geographical distribution==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Public Health Unit\n!Cases\n!Resolved\n!{{tooltip|Per m|Total cases per million inhabitants}}\n!Deaths\n!Ref\n|-\n|[[Algoma District|Algoma]]\n|6\n|\n|{{Round| {{#expr:6/ 0.113}} |2}}\n|\n|[http://www.algomapublichealth.com/disease-and-illness/infectious-diseases/novel-coronavirus/] [https://www.sootoday.com/coronavirus-covid-19-sault-ste-marie-news/second-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-algoma-2207915]\n|-\n|[[County of Brant|Brant County]] (including [[Brantford]])\n|29\n|\n|{{Round| {{#expr:29/ 0.135}} |2}}\n|1\n|[https://www.bchu.org/ServicesWeProvide/InfectiousDiseases/Pages/coronavirus.aspx] [https://www.bchu.org/Media/Pages/first-death-covid19.aspx]\n|-\n|[[Chatham-Kent]]\n|10\n|1\n|{{Round| {{#expr:9/ 0.102}} |2}}\n|0\n|[https://ckphu.com/covid-19/]\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]]\n|173\n|15\n|{{Round| {{#expr:173 / 0.65}} |2}}\n|9\n|[https://www.durham.ca/en/health-and-wellness/novel-coronavirus-update.aspx]\n|-\n|[[Eastern Ontario]] ([[Stormont, Dundas and Glengarry]]-[[Prescott and Russell]])\n|26\n|\n|{{Round| {{#expr:26/ 0.203}} |2}}\n| \n|[https://eohu.ca/en/my-health/covid-19-status-update-for-eohu-region]\n|-\n|[[Grey County|Grey]] [[Bruce County|Bruce]]\n|15\n|5\n|{{Round| {{#expr:15/ 0.162}} |2}}\n|\n|[https://www.publichealthgreybruce.on.ca/]\n|-\n|[[Haldim