jwyWT4q8YhoBRyx01aFXJwIUdNKUIha-usbnX6clOm05JBsMrtv814yDxEUISLoka-p5LmgW7WPSWfhO0Pf80YQTCzsggMTJzBsDIOujuaXBMOwOp7uQgDeBIN_bz_c9bGnw8hA5Hb9DBFEdglPUWximtrpkmnUMqlm6TjRaLrsaOYSIO1YGOs2PWcnQu7kBsVVsUhyIZmQbajy4lVtSsnl4XKwyTOmZka3ctMGLlYsUZQOZcpLRktWUpHuCnZUuYpoG5L8yFO9-x188rpx8TMvuDIcUPWkLiVWLeyrLR4NND9ydkJTkReZeoqnXyrl1XbQ_9ihBt5sFN6GZuGNZuH_R5zAB1d3FPzQHJjgGL6Le2aAw7BZ7cNmtQ-b1T5s9t_P_ipOUOeZypSNYuyO1wqWyo2m3C1HUY3HoejL2n4CFPOX_Z44ylPPRvomUdSoqe6yaYbNShPvvVAbukt8el5lt5Z5vzo5rdYHUF08-Q!!/dz/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/#.XnTdr8jYrnE]\n|-\n|}\n\nUpdated as of April 3, 2020.\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:Father Michael McGivney Catholic Academy sign during COVID-19 shutdown.jpg|thumb|Notice of school closure at a [[York Catholic District School Board|YCDSB]] high school in [[Markham, Ontario]]]]\n[[File:Personal Protective Equipment donation tent at North York General Hospital - 20200326.jpg|thumb|Personal Protective Equipment donation tent at [[North York General Hospital]].]]\nOntario has announced they have a dedicated web page updated thrice daily with the cumulative total and new cases.<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/>  In addition, they have been making new releases as cases are confirmed, with their source whether they are due to travel history or close contact.<ref>{{cite web |title=Newsroom : News: Health |url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en |website=news.ontario.ca |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310003242/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health (Ontario)|Ontario Minister of Health and Long-Term Care]], [[Christine Elliott]], has been overseeing the emergency plan for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|title=Ontario government has a coronavirus outbreak plan but won't reveal details|last=Ferguson|first=Rob|date=2020-03-09|website=Toronto.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174116/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the Government of Ontario announced publicly funded schools would be closed for an additional two weeks after [[Spring break|March Break]] until April 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|title=Ontario to shut down publicly funded schools for 2 weeks after March Break over COVID-19 concerns|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318155003/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, The Ontario Superior Court of Justice announced a suspension of most criminal matters, including trials until the end of May.<ref>{{cite web |title=Notice to Accused Persons, Profession, Crown, Public Prosecution Service of Canada, Correctional Institutions, Witnesses, Jurors, The Public and The Media Regarding Criminal Operations |url=https://www.ontariocourts.ca/scj/covid-19-suspension-crim/ |website=www.ontariocourts.ca |publisher=Superior Court of Justice}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Ontario Premier [[Doug Ford]] declared a province-wide [[state of emergency]].<ref name=\"emergency\"/> This included prohibition of all public events of over 50 people (later reduced to 5 people on March 28), closure of bars and restaurants (with the exception that restaurants may continue to provide takeout and delivery services) as well as libraries, theatres, cinemas, private schools (in addition to publicly-funded schools which were already been ordered closed from March 14 until further notice) and daycares.<ref name=\"death\"/><ref name=\"gatheringban5\" /> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|title=Region of Peel declares Emergency to protect health and safety of residents and staff|publisher=peelregion.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320180506/https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Simcoe County]] by Warden George Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|title=County of Simcoe declares COVID-19 emergency|publisher=simcoe.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20 further measures were announced including waiving the three months waiting period for health care coverage,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|title=Ontario Expands Coverage for Care|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200921/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the launch of an e-learning portal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|title=Ontario Helping Students Learn from the Safety of Their Own Home|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200922/https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and extended privileges for hospitals to re-deploy staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|title=Ontario Takes Extraordinary Steps to Ensure Health Care Resources are Available to Contain COVID-19|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200924/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Ford announced that all \"non-essential\" businesses be ordered closed starting 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 24. Ford also stated that schools would remain closed past the original April 6 opening date and until further notice.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| title = Ontario schools will not reopen April 6, premier says| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323185123/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://nationalpost.com/news/covid-19-ontario-and-quebec-order-non-essential-businesses-closed-after-spike-in-coronavirus-totals| title = COVID-19: Ontario and Quebec order non-essential businesses closed after spike in coronavirus totals| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = }}</ref> A list of 74 \"essential\" businesses was published later in the day on March 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|title=Ford says list of essential businesses amid COVID-19 pandemic is 'adjustable'|date=2020-03-24|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181806/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|title=Ontario government releases list of essential workplaces that can remain open|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325165046/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|title=Ontario orders all non-essential businesses to shut down|date=2020-03-23|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325193928/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, a state of emergency was declared in Toronto by Mayor [[John Tory]],<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| title = Toronto declares state of emergency amid COVID-19 pandemic| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323192730/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet| user=JohnTory| number=1242165183465783306| author=John Tory| date=March 23, 2020| title=We are declaring a State of Emergency as part of the City's ongoing efforts to stop the spread of COVID-19 and to ensure the municipal government can continue to act and respond quickly to the pandemic and any other events that arise in the weeks ahead.}}</ref> in [[Regional Municipality of York|York Region]] by Chair Wayne Emmerson,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.york.ca/wps/portal/yorkhome/newsroom/mediarelease/yorkregionchairmanandceowayneemmersondeclaresstateofemergencyacrosstheregionalmunicipalityofyork/|title=York Region Chairman and CEO Wayne Emmerson declares state of emergency across The Regional Municipality of York|publisher=york.ca| date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] by Chair Gary Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|title=Regional Chair declares state of emergency in response to COVID-19|publisher=halton.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191011/https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]] by Chair John Henry<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durham.ca/modules/news/index.aspx?newsId=0237de13-9c0c-4eb6-9624-71d1607e3472|title=Durham Region declares state of emergency|publisher=durham.ca|date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Kawartha Lakes]] by Mayor Andy Letham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|title=COVID-19 Update 19 Video Message from Mayor Letham on Declaration of State of Emergency|publisher=kawarthalakes.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Ford and [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Finance Minister]] [[Rod Phillips (politician)|Rod Phillips]] introduced a $17-billion response package that includes an influx of cash for the health sector, direct payments to parents and tax breaks for businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|title=Ontario introduces $17B COVID-19 package; more than doubles deficit in fiscal update|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180709/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, a municipal state of emergency was declared in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] by Mayor [[Bryan Paterson]] due to two new cases of the virus announced by [[KFL&A Public Health]]. Three recent cases in [[Lennox and Addington County|the region]] had reported no prior close contact with known infected persons, causing health officials to conclude that community transmission is present in the region, and closures of several medical clinics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|title=Community spread of COVID-19 confirmed, Kingston region declares states of emergency|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180149/https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, following California and British Columbia, takeout and delivery orders from restaurants can include alcoholic beverages as long as the order contains food items and is ordered between 9 a.m. and 11 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|title=Info Bulletin No. 61: Liquor sales licensees may now sell liquor for takeout or delivery along with food &#124; Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario|website=www.agco.ca|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327030841/https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27 at 2:00&nbsp;p.m. ET, [[Alert Ready]] was activated on all radio stations, television channels and providers, and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] wireless networks in Ontario, to distribute a warning informing travellers returning to Ontario of the mandatory self-isolation requirements under federal law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|title=Ontario issuing emergency alert on COVID-19 to phones, radios and TVs|work=[[CBC News]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327185645/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the anticipated increase in patients requiring critical care, the Ontario government announced on March 27 that over 3,000 ventilators are ready to be deployed in Ontario (compared to the current capacity of approximately 1,300 critical care beds with ventilators and 43 patients requiring critical care as of March 27).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6742260/coronavirus-ontario-hospitals-ventilators-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus: Up to 3,250 ventilators ready to be deployed in Ontario, officials say|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the Ontario government extended the state of emergency through April 13, and also ordered the province-wide closure of all outdoor recreational amenities, including beaches, playgrounds and sports facilities (several Ontario municipalities including Toronto, had already ordered similar closures of their recreational amenities several days prior to the province-wide order).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6754560/coronavirus-ontario-outdoor-recreation-amenities-closure-order/|title=Coronavirus: Ontario government orders shutdown of all outdoor recreation amenities|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On March 31, it was announced that the schools would remain closed until at least May 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-students-covid19-1.5516104|title=Ontario unveils details of learn-at-home program, students out of school until at least May 4|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The same day, John Tory announced that the City of Toronto would cancel all city-led major events, festivals (including [[Pride Toronto|Toronto's gay pride parade]] which was scheduled to take place on June 28), conferences, permits and cultural programs until June 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6758350/coronavirus-toronto-cancels-events-pride-parade/|title=Coronavirus: City of Toronto cancels events through June 30, including Pride Parade|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Tory also clarified that major sporting events held in Toronto, such as [[Toronto Blue Jays]] baseball games, are not specifically prohibited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2020/03/toronto-bans-public-events-june-30-blue-jays.html|title=City Of Toronto Announces Events Ban|website=MLB Trade Rumors}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nOn March 18, The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that test results announced by the provincial government were several days old, with turnaround times increasing from 24 hours to 4 days, leading the government to \"making decisions based on old information\".<ref name=\"starbacklog\">{{cite web| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| title=Huge backlog in COVID-19 test results means Ontario is making decisions based on old information| date=March 18, 2020| first=Kevin| last=Donovan| url-status=live| archive-date=March 19, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319001515/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The same story reported that the government's goal of performing 5,000 tests per day may be two weeks away.<ref name=\"starbacklog\"/> The province was only able to process around 2,000 tests per day by March 19, which caused the backlog.<ref name=\"urlConcerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario | CBC News\"/>\n\nThe backlog increased to over 8,000 unprocessed samples on March 24 with patients waiting at least four days for results, partially due to fact that private and university laboratories are not allowed to process samples.<ref name=\"urlWhy Ontarios COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus | CBC News\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |title=Why Ontario's COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324171047/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)]\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=1cWm99ZSIeceKzu97rk50ik32cSvvX4pa&ll=44.45836936528724%2C-79.37585575178662&z=8 Map of COVID-19 cases and related closures at a regional level across Canada]\n*[http://covidcanada.ca/?p=ON Covid Canada] - Graph of data for spread of virus in Ontario and live news feed.\n*[https://dynamicmt.com/COVID-19-ON Chart of COVID-19 daily case count for Ontario]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{portalbar|Medicine|Ontario|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada by province or territory|Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ontario|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Ontario}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case      = [[Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre|Sunnybrook Hospital]], [[Toronto]]\n| confirmed_cases = 3,255<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/>\n| deaths          = 67<ref name=\"Ontario_official\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus |title=The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |website=ontario.ca |access-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228004601/https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus |archive-date=February 28, 2020 }}</ref>, 81 ([https://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/coronavirustracker/]), 92 ([[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario#Geographical distribution|PC]]) or 98 ([https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/03/health-officials-in-peel-region-accidentally-mail-wrong-covid-19-test-results-ontario-to-reveal-projection-numbers-today-stars-count-says-ontario-has-3210-cases-92-deaths.html])\n| recovery_cases  = 1,023<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/>\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date    = January 25, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=25|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| location        = [[Ontario]], Canada\n| website         = [https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus Ontario Government]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ontario''' is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a [[novel virus|novel]] infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|COVID-19 in Canada]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 worldwide pandemic]] occurred in the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Ontario]], and was confirmed on January 27, 2020, after a man returned to [[Toronto]] from travel in [[China]], including [[Wuhan]]. As of April 2 at 4&nbsp;p.m. ET,<!-- Updated by Government of Ontario every morning at 10:30 and afternoon at 5:30 --> there have been 3,255 confirmed cases, 1,023 recoveries, and 67 deaths.<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-new-covid-19-cases-total-sunday-1.5498410|title=Ontario confirms 39 new COVID-19 cases, bringing provincial total to 142|date=March 15, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"death\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-covid-19-ontario-tuesday-1.5500006 |title=1st death confirmed in Ontario as province declares state of emergency over COVID-19 &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref> Overall 57,874 people have been tested for the virus, with 60,681 people (95.6%) testing negative and 2,793 people (4.4%) testing positive,<ref name=\"Ontario_official\"/> the remaining people are still waiting on their test results due to a backlog in testing.<ref name=\"starbacklog\"/><ref name=\"urlConcerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario | CBC News\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-19-coronavirus-ontario-testing-delays-wait-time-1.5502605 |title=Concerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320161216/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-19-coronavirus-ontario-testing-delays-wait-time-1.5502605 |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of April 3, of all cases 381 have been hospitalized and 116 required intensive care.<ref name=\"Report-2020-03-29\">{{cite web |url=https://files.ontario.ca/moh-covid-19-report-en-2020-03-31.pdf |title=files.ontario.ca |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Government of Ontario declared a state of emergency,<ref name=\"emergency\">{{cite news |last1=Rodrigues |first1=Gabby |title=Ontario government declares state of emergency amid coronavirus pandemic |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6688074/ontario-doug-ford-coronavirus-covid-19-march-17/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=Global News |agency=Corus Entertainment |date=March 17, 2020 |language=en-CA}}</ref> closing bars and restaurants (with the exception of take-out and delivery services), as well as libraries, theatres, cinemas, schools and daycares and all public gatherings of more than 50 people (later reduced to 5 people on March 28).<ref name=\"death\"/><ref name=\"gatheringban5\">{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6746181/ontario-ban-gatherings/|title=Ontario government bans gatherings of 5 or more people in bid to stop coronavirus spread|website=Global News|access-date=28 March 2020|date=28 March 2020|last1=Rocca|first1=Ryan|last2=Shah|first2=Maryam|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, the government announced on March 17 that Ontario had \"some evidence of community transmission\" of COVID-19.<ref name=\"urlToronto waking up to new reality amid evidence of COVID-19 community spread | CBC News\">{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-waking-up-to-new-reality-amid-evidence-of-covid-19-community-spread-1.5499768| title=Toronto waking up to new reality amid 'evidence' of COVID-19 community spread by prof. Doctor Aman ALBARGHOUTI| first=Lauren| last=Pelley| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200320015455/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-waking-up-to-new-reality-amid-evidence-of-covid-19-community-spread-1.5499768| archive-date=March 20, 2020| date=March 17, 2020| accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3rd, the Ontario government released projections indicating 3 000 to 15 000 deaths were possible unless further measures were taken.  The same models indicated that had no measures been taken whatsoever, the death toll could have reached 100 000.<ref>https://www.cp24.com/news/3-000-to-15-000-could-die-in-ontario-due-to-covid-19-provincial-modelling-1.4880754</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Canada/Ontario medical cases chart}}\n\n===January\u2013February===\nOn January 23, the first presumptive case in Canada was admitted to [[Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre]] in [[Toronto]] and placed into a negative pressure chamber.<ref name=\"RC\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/01/ontario-confirms-first-case-of-wuhan-novel-coronavirus.html|title=Ontario Confirms First Case of Wuhan Novel Coronavirus|date=January 25, 2020|work=|accessdate=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129194142/https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1496143/coronavirus-confirmation-2e-cas-toronto|archive-date=29 January 2020|publisher=Government of Ontario|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/tracking-every-case-of-covid-19-in-canada-1.4852102|title=Tracking every case of COVID-19 in Canada|date=2020-03-13|website=Coronavirus|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315124205/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/tracking-every-case-of-covid-19-in-canada-1.4852102|archive-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The patient, a male in his 50s who travelled between Wuhan and [[Guangzhou]] before returning to Toronto on January 22, contacted emergency services following rapid onset symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6462626/coronavirus-toronto-hospital/|title=Health officials to announce 'presumptive case' of coronavirus in Toronto|website=Global News|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125222207/https://globalnews.ca/news/6462626/coronavirus-toronto-hospital/|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The presumption of infection in the patient was made after a rapid test was done at [[Public Health Ontario]]'s Toronto laboratory. Final testing conducted at the [[National Microbiology Laboratory]] in Winnipeg, [[Manitoba]] confirmed the presumptive case on January 25.<ref name=\"RC\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Authorities said that the patient was experiencing respiratory problems but was in stable condition.<ref name=\"RC\"/> His condition later improved and he was released from hospital on January 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|title=Canada's 1st coronavirus patient discharged from Toronto hospital|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131165249/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, the Chief Medical Officer of Health of [[Ontario]] announced the man's wife as the second presumptive case.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=2nd presumptive case of coronavirus confirmed in Ontario|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-wuhan-ontario-second-case-1.5441401|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=27 January 2020|date=27 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127133636/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-wuhan-ontario-second-case-1.5441401|archive-date=27 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials reported that she was in good condition and that she was asymptomatic.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn January 31, the third case in [[Ontario]] (and the fourth case in Canada) was reported in the city of [[London, Ontario|London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6489956/3rd-case-coronavirus-confirmed-ontario/|title=Woman in her 20s confirmed as 3rd case of coronavirus in Ontario|website=Global News|access-date=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|last1=Patton|first1=Jessica|last2=Dhanraj|first2=Travis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201045003/https://globalnews.ca/news/6489956/3rd-case-coronavirus-confirmed-ontario/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials said that the individual, a woman in her 20s and a student at [[University of Western Ontario]], returned from Wuhan on January 23.<ref name=\"CBC2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|title=Ontario confirms 3rd coronavirus patient, Toronto hospital discharges the 1st one|last=Boisvert|first=Nick|publisher=CBC News|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=31 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131165249/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/sunnybrook-coronavirus-patient-1.5447251|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She was [[asymptomatic]] and had tested negative at first, but additional advanced testing confirmed that the woman had low levels of the virus in her system.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/> Officials said that the individual wore a mask during her voyage and she voluntarily entered self-isolation upon her return, making a full recovery after two or three days.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/> On the same day, the [[Government of Ontario]] reported that 17 cases were under investigation within its provincial jurisdiction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov|title=The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|website=Government of Ontario|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131014611/https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-ncov|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials said that most of the individuals under investigation were awaiting results while in self-isolation at home.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-ontario-toronto-update-public-health-1.5445620|title=No new cases of coronavirus in Ontario, public health officials say|publisher=CBC News|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130152659/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-ontario-toronto-update-public-health-1.5445620|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 30, the associate medical officer of Ontario said that the province had conducted a total of 67 tests with 38 negative results.<ref name=\"CBC\"/> Officials said that all possible cases\u2014including previous negative results\u2014were being retested as additional assessments become available.<ref name=\"CBC2\"/>\n\n[[CFB Trenton]] in [[Trenton, Ontario]] has been used as a quarantine facility for repatriated Canadians since February 7.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/happy-to-be-back-flight-carrying-canadians-from-wuhan-lands-in-ontario-1.4801361|title= 'Happy to be back': Flight carrying Canadians from Wuhan lands in Ontario|publisher=ctvnews.ca|date=7 February 2020}}</ref> As of March 20, 12 positive cases for the virus of the repatriated citizens at CFB Trenton have been reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/victoria-grand-princess-passenger-says-12-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-quarantine-1.4862142|title=Victoria Grand Princess passenger says 12 diagnosed with COVID-19 in quarantine|publisher=vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320231507/https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/victoria-grand-princess-passenger-says-12-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-quarantine-1.4862142|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, a fourth presumptive case in Ontario was announced of a woman in her 20s who presented to a hospital on February 21 with symptoms after travelling to Wuhan. The woman was tested locally with a positive test result and the sample was sent to the [[National Microbiology Laboratory]] in [[Winnipeg]].<ref name=\"20200224urlHealthofficials_CBCNews\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-update-1.5473473 |title=Health officials say system to manage coronavirus is 'working quite well' amid 4th case in Ontario &#124; CBC News |accessdate=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201033/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-update-1.5473473 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 24, health officials in Ontario stated that all three previous cases in Ontario were \"resolved\", which means patients had two consecutive negative test results 24 hours apart and that the \"system was working\".<ref name=\"20200224urlHealthofficials_CBCNews\"/>\n\n===March===\n[[File:Leslie street on a Thursday morning during the COVID-19 pandemic - 1.jpg|thumb|[[Leslie Street]] empty at 9:00 a.m. on a weekday in Toronto.]]\n[[File:YRTReducedScheduleNotice.jpg|thumb|[[York Region Transit]] bus schedule reduction in March]]\nOn March 5, Ontario reported three more cases of the virus, for a total of 23 in the province, with cases in [[Toronto]], [[Kitchener, ON|Kitchener]], and [[Mississauga, ON|Mississauga]] being reported. The three cases came from [[Iran]], [[Italy]], and the [[Grand Princess|''Grand Princess'' cruise ship]], respectively. It was also announced that another case in Ontario was resolved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-confirms-3-new-cases-coronavirus-1.5486670|title=Ontario confirms 3 new cases of coronavirus, bringing total to 23 in province|date=5 March 2020|website=Toronto|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221134501/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-confirms-3-new-cases-coronavirus-1.5486670|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFive cases, two imported from each of Iran and the ''Grand Princess'', and one from Las Vegas, were reported on March 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6640864/ontario-new-coronavirus-cases/|title=Officials announce new cases of COVID-19 in Ontario for total of 28|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135041/https://globalnews.ca/news/6640864/ontario-new-coronavirus-cases/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Four more cases were reported to have been imported from Colorado, [[Washington, D.C.]], France, and Germany on March 8, bringing the total to 32.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6647308/ontario-coronavirus-woman-travelled-colorado/|title=Ontario reports additional case of COVID-19, woman who travelled to Colorado|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309135022/https://globalnews.ca/news/6647308/ontario-coronavirus-woman-travelled-colorado/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-reports-two-more-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-the-total-to-31-1.4843941|title=Ontario reports two more cases of COVID-19, bringing the total to 31|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9879814--risk-to-peel-citizens-is-still-low-peel-region-reports-third-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus/ |title='Risk to Peel citizens is still low': Peel Region reports third confirmed case of coronavirus |publisher=Toronto.com |accessdate=2020-03-08 |date=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153828/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9879814--risk-to-peel-citizens-is-still-low-peel-region-reports-third-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Ontario confirmed two new cases of coronavirus, bringing the total number of cases in the province to 34. They are an octogenarian and a septuagenarian from Toronto having travelled to Iran, where cases of COVID-19 had multiplied in recent weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1654787/coronavirus-ontario-32-cas-peel-voyage-allemagne|title=34 cas de coronavirus en Ontario, 4 gu\u00e9risons {{!}} Coronavirus : Ontario|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone Soci\u00e9t\u00e9-|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, a close contact of a previous case and a man who travelled to Switzerland were confirmed as Ontario's 35th and 36th case, respectively. Later the same day, a Sudbury man who attended the [[Prospectors & Developers Association of Canada]] (PDAC) conference in Toronto on March 2\u20133 was confirmed as the 37th positive case, and the first in northern Ontario.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sudbury man who attended Toronto convention confirmed as Ontario's 37th coronavirus case |author=Rodriguez, Gabby |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6655133/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-36-case-switzerland/amp/ |work=Global News |date=2020-03-10 |accessdate=2020-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311164407/https://globalnews.ca/news/6655133/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-36-case-switzerland/amp/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, a 40-year-old man who recently travelled to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]] was confirmed as the first coronavirus case in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 1st case of COVID-19 reported in Ottawa |author=Rocca, Ryan |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6660518/ottawa-first-coronavirus-case/ |work=Global News |date=2020-03-11 |accessdate=2020-03-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312154951/https://globalnews.ca/news/6660518/ottawa-first-coronavirus-case/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The overall coronavirus case number in Ontario rose to 42 on the same day. On March 12, 17 new cases were confirmed including a baby boy who had recently visited the [[North York General Hospital]] in Toronto. That day, the total number of cases in Ontario increased to 59.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/17-more-cases-of-covid-19-including-a-baby-boy-confirmed-in-ontario-1.4850170| title=17 more cases of COVID-19, including a baby boy, confirmed in Ontario| first=Sean| last=Davidson| date=March 12, 2020| website=ctvnews.ca| access-date=March 12, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313015745/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/17-more-cases-of-covid-19-including-a-baby-boy-confirmed-in-ontario-1.4850170| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On March 13, health officials reported 19 additional cases, bringing the number of cases to 79, and on the 14th, 24 more, making the total 103.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rodrigues|first=Gabby|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6671583/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-cases-march-13/|title=Ontario confirms 19 new cases of coronavirus, bringing provincial total to 79|date=March 13, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134544/https://globalnews.ca/news/6671583/ontario-coronavirus-covid19-cases-march-13/|archive-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> On March 17, it was announced that a man in his 70s, who had died in [[Barrie]], was the first death in Ontario as a result of COVID-19.<ref name=\"death\"/> On March 18, a player for the [[Ottawa Senators]] hockey team was tested positive.<ref name=\"ottsenpositive\">{{cite news |last1=March 18 |first1=Bruce Garrioch Updated: |title=Ottawa Senators player becomes first NHLer to test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-senators-player-tests-positive-covid-19 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Ottawa Citizen |publisher=Postmedia |date=18 March 2020 |language=en-CA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318081809/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/ottawa-senators-player-tests-positive-covid-19 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 23 new cases were confirmed in Ontario that day, bringing the total number of cases to 212.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/23-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-ontario-bringing-provincial-total-to-212-1.4857982| title=23 new cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Ontario, bringing provincial total to 212| first=Sean| last=Davidson| date=March 18, 2020| website=ctvnews.ca| url-status=live| archive-date=March 18, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173356/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/23-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-ontario-bringing-provincial-total-to-212-1.4857982| access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom the initial case on January 23 to March 18, over half of the reported cases are reported in [[Toronto]] (220 cases),<ref name=\"urlCOVID-19 \u2013 City of Toronto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/home/covid-19/ |title=COVID-19 \u2013 City of Toronto |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321014118/https://www.toronto.ca/home/covid-19/ |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> of which 11 are under investigation for community transmission.<ref name=\"url11 hospitalized as coronavirus cases rise to 128 in Toronto | News\">{{cite web |url=https://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-coronavirus-pandemic-new-cases-hospitilization |title=11 hospitalized as coronavirus cases rise to 128 in Toronto &#124; News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320152521/https://dailyhive.com/toronto/toronto-coronavirus-pandemic-new-cases-hospitilization |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] reported 23 cases<ref name=\"urlNovel Coronavirus (COVID-19) | City of Hamilton, Ontario, Canada\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hamilton.ca/public-health/covid-19/novel-coronavirus-covid-19 |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) &#124; City of Hamilton, Ontario, Canada |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150745/https://www.hamilton.ca/public-health/covid-19/novel-coronavirus-covid-19 |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Ottawa]] 19 cases,<ref name=\"urlNovel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Ottawa Public Health\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ottawapublichealth.ca/en/public-health-topics/novel-coronavirus.aspx |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Ottawa Public Health |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319013757/https://www.ottawapublichealth.ca/en/public-health-topics/novel-coronavirus.aspx |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham]] reported 18 cases<ref name=\"urlCOVID-19 Update - Region of Durham\">{{cite web |url=https://www.durham.ca/en/health-and-wellness/novel-coronavirus-update.aspx |title=COVID-19 Update - Region of Durham |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320152830/https://www.durham.ca/en/health-and-wellness/novel-coronavirus-update.aspx |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]] reporting 14 cases.<ref name=\"urlConfirmed positive cases in Waterloo Region - Region of Waterloo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/health-and-wellness/confirmed-positive-cases-in-waterloo-region.aspx |title=Confirmed positive cases in Waterloo Region - Region of Waterloo |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320150737/https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/health-and-wellness/confirmed-positive-cases-in-waterloo-region.aspx |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn April 2, [[Lakeridge Health]] declared an outbreak of COVID-19 at [[Lakeridge Health Oshawa]] in [[Oshawa, Ontario|Oshawa]], and announced that one of its in-patient units would be temporarily closed after a hospital-acquired case of COVID-19 was transmitted to a health care worker treating the patient.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freeman |first1=Joshua |title=Lakeridge Health declares COVID-19 outbreak at Oshawa Hospital |url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/lakeridge-health-declares-covid-19-outbreak-at-oshawa-hospital-1.4880155 |website=CTV News |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geographical distribution==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Public Health Unit\n!Cases\n!Resolved\n!{{tooltip|Per m|Total cases per million inhabitants}}\n!Deaths\n!Ref\n|-\n|[[Algoma District|Algoma]]\n|6\n|\n|{{Round| {{#expr:6/ 0.113}} |2}}\n|\n|[http://www.algomapublichealth.com/disease-and-illness/infectious-diseases/novel-coronavirus/] [https://www.sootoday.com/coronavirus-covid-19-sault-ste-marie-news/second-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-algoma-2207915]\n|-\n|[[County of Brant|Brant County]] (including [[Brantford]])\n|29\n|\n|{{Round| {{#expr:29/ 0.135}} |2}}\n|1\n|[https://www.bchu.org/ServicesWeProvide/InfectiousDiseases/Pages/coronavirus.aspx] [https://www.bchu.org/Media/Pages/first-death-covid19.aspx]\n|-\n|[[Chatham-Kent]]\n|10\n|1\n|{{Round| {{#expr:9/ 0.102}} |2}}\n|0\n|[https://ckphu.com/covid-19/]\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]]\n|173\