/en |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health (Ontario)|Ontario Minister of Health and Long-Term Care]], [[Christine Elliott]], has been overseeing the emergency plan for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|title=Ontario government has a coronavirus outbreak plan but won't reveal details|last=Ferguson|first=Rob|date=2020-03-09|website=Toronto.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174116/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9881027-ontario-government-has-a-coronavirus-outbreak-plan-but-won-t-reveal-details/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the Government of Ontario announced publicly funded schools would be closed for an additional two weeks after [[Spring break|March Break]] until April 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|title=Ontario to shut down publicly funded schools for 2 weeks after March Break over COVID-19 concerns|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318155003/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-government-closing-schools-1.5495736|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, The Ontario Superior Court of Justice announced a suspension of most criminal matters, including trials until the end of May.<ref>{{cite web |title=Notice to Accused Persons, Profession, Crown, Public Prosecution Service of Canada, Correctional Institutions, Witnesses, Jurors, The Public and The Media Regarding Criminal Operations |url=https://www.ontariocourts.ca/scj/covid-19-suspension-crim/ |website=www.ontariocourts.ca |publisher=Superior Court of Justice}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Ontario Premier [[Doug Ford]] declared a province-wide [[state of emergency]].<ref name=\"emergency\"/> This included prohibition of all public events of over 50 people (later reduced to 5 people on March 28), closure of bars and restaurants (with the exception that restaurants may continue to provide takeout and delivery services) as well as libraries, theatres, cinemas, private schools (in addition to publicly-funded schools which were already been ordered closed from March 14 until further notice) and daycares.<ref name=\"death\"/><ref name=\"gatheringban5\" /> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|title=Region of Peel declares Emergency to protect health and safety of residents and staff|publisher=peelregion.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320180506/https://peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2020&month=2&day=18&file=2020218.xml|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Simcoe County]] by Warden George Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|title=County of Simcoe declares COVID-19 emergency|publisher=simcoe.ca|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.simcoe.ca/CorporateCommunications/Pages/county-of-simcoe-declares-covid-19-emergency-20-3-18.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20 further measures were announced including waiving the three months waiting period for health care coverage,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|title=Ontario Expands Coverage for Care|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200921/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-expands-coverage-for-care.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the launch of an e-learning portal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|title=Ontario Helping Students Learn from the Safety of Their Own Home|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200922/https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2020/03/ontario-helping-students-learn-from-the-safety-of-their-own-home.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and extended privileges for hospitals to re-deploy staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|title=Ontario Takes Extraordinary Steps to Ensure Health Care Resources are Available to Contain COVID-19|website=news.ontario.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322200924/https://news.ontario.ca/mohltc/en/2020/03/ontario-takes-extraordinary-steps-to-ensure-health-care-resources-are-available-to-contain-covid-19.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Ford announced that all \"non-essential\" businesses be ordered closed starting 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 24. Ford also stated that schools would remain closed past the original April 6 opening date and until further notice.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| title = Ontario schools will not reopen April 6, premier says| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323185123/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-schools-will-not-reopen-april-6-premier-says-1.4864551| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://nationalpost.com/news/covid-19-ontario-and-quebec-order-non-essential-businesses-closed-after-spike-in-coronavirus-totals| title = COVID-19: Ontario and Quebec order non-essential businesses closed after spike in coronavirus totals| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = }}</ref> A list of 74 \"essential\" businesses was published later in the day on March 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|title=Ford says list of essential businesses amid COVID-19 pandemic is 'adjustable'|date=2020-03-24|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181806/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ford-says-list-of-essential-businesses-amid-covid-19-pandemic-is-adjustable-1.4865528|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|title=Ontario government releases list of essential workplaces that can remain open|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325165046/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-list-essential-businesses-1.5507687|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|title=Ontario orders all non-essential businesses to shut down|date=2020-03-23|website=CTV News Toronto|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325193928/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-orders-all-non-essential-businesses-to-shut-down-1.4864492|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, a state of emergency was declared in Toronto by Mayor [[John Tory]],<ref>{{cite web| url = https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| title = Toronto declares state of emergency amid COVID-19 pandemic| date = March 23, 2020| access-date = March 23, 2020| language = en| trans-title = | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323192730/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/toronto-declares-state-of-emergency-amid-covid-19-pandemic-1.4864679| archive-date = March 23, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet| user=JohnTory| number=1242165183465783306| author=John Tory| date=March 23, 2020| title=We are declaring a State of Emergency as part of the City's ongoing efforts to stop the spread of COVID-19 and to ensure the municipal government can continue to act and respond quickly to the pandemic and any other events that arise in the weeks ahead.}}</ref> in [[Regional Municipality of York|York Region]] by Chair Wayne Emmerson,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.york.ca/wps/portal/yorkhome/newsroom/mediarelease/yorkregionchairmanandceowayneemmersondeclaresstateofemergencyacrosstheregionalmunicipalityofyork/|title=York Region Chairman and CEO Wayne Emmerson declares state of emergency across The Regional Municipality of York|publisher=york.ca| date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] by Chair Gary Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|title=Regional Chair declares state of emergency in response to COVID-19|publisher=halton.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191011/https://www.halton.ca/The-Region/News/2020/Regional-Chair-declares-state-of-emergency-in-resp|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, a state of emergency was also declared in [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]] by Chair John Henry<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durham.ca/modules/news/index.aspx?newsId=0237de13-9c0c-4eb6-9624-71d1607e3472|title=Durham Region declares state of emergency|publisher=durham.ca|date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Kawartha Lakes]] by Mayor Andy Letham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|title=COVID-19 Update 19 Video Message from Mayor Letham on Declaration of State of Emergency|publisher=kawarthalakes.ca|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191008/https://www.kawarthalakes.ca/en/news/covid-19-update-19-video-message-from-mayor-letham-on-declaration-of-state-of-emergency.aspx|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Ford and [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Finance Minister]] [[Rod Phillips (politician)|Rod Phillips]] introduced a $17-billion response package that includes an influx of cash for the health sector, direct payments to parents and tax breaks for businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|title=Ontario introduces $17B COVID-19 package; more than doubles deficit in fiscal update|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180709/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/2020-fiscal-update-1.5510186|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, a municipal state of emergency was declared in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] by Mayor [[Bryan Paterson]] due to two new cases of the virus announced by [[KFL&A Public Health]]. Three recent cases in [[Lennox and Addington County|the region]] had reported no prior close contact with known infected persons, causing health officials to conclude that community transmission is present in the region, and closures of several medical clinics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|title=Community spread of COVID-19 confirmed, Kingston region declares states of emergency|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326180149/https://globalnews.ca/news/6736452/community-spread-of-covid-19-confirmed-city-of-kingston-declares-state-of-emergency/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, following California and British Columbia, takeout and delivery orders from restaurants can include alcoholic beverages as long as the order contains food items and is ordered between 9 a.m. and 11 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|title=Info Bulletin No. 61: Liquor sales licensees may now sell liquor for takeout or delivery along with food &#124; Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario|website=www.agco.ca|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327030841/https://www.agco.ca/bulletin/2020/info-bulletin-no-61-liquor-sales-licensees-may-now-sell-liquor-takeout-or-delivery|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27 at 2:00&nbsp;p.m. ET, [[Alert Ready]] was activated on all radio stations, television channels and providers, and [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] wireless networks in Ontario, to distribute a warning informing travellers returning to Ontario of the mandatory self-isolation requirements under federal law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|title=Ontario issuing emergency alert on COVID-19 to phones, radios and TVs|work=[[CBC News]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327185645/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/coronavirus-alert-1.5512525|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the anticipated increase in patients requiring critical care, the Ontario government announced on March 27 that over 3,000 ventilators are ready to be deployed in Ontario (compared to the current capacity of approximately 1,300 critical care beds with ventilators and 43 patients requiring critical care as of March 27).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6742260/coronavirus-ontario-hospitals-ventilators-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus: Up to 3,250 ventilators ready to be deployed in Ontario, officials say|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the Ontario government extended the state of emergency through April 13, and also ordered the province-wide closure of all outdoor recreational amenities, including beaches, playgrounds and sports facilities (several Ontario municipalities including Toronto, had already ordered similar closures of their recreational amenities several days prior to the province-wide order).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6754560/coronavirus-ontario-outdoor-recreation-amenities-closure-order/|title=Coronavirus: Ontario government orders shutdown of all outdoor recreation amenities|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On March 31, it was announced that the schools would remain closed until at least May 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ontario-students-covid19-1.5516104|title=Ontario unveils details of learn-at-home program, students out of school until at least May 4|publisher=cbc.ca|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The same day, John Tory announced that the City of Toronto would cancel all city-led major events, festivals (including [[Pride Toronto|Toronto's gay pride parade]] which was scheduled to take place on June 28), conferences, permits and cultural programs until June 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6758350/coronavirus-toronto-cancels-events-pride-parade/|title=Coronavirus: City of Toronto cancels events through June 30, including Pride Parade|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Tory also clarified that major sporting events held in Toronto, such as [[Toronto Blue Jays]] baseball games, are not specifically prohibited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2020/03/toronto-bans-public-events-june-30-blue-jays.html|title=City Of Toronto Announces Events Ban|website=MLB Trade Rumors}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nOn March 18, The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that test results announced by the provincial government were several days old, with turnaround times increasing from 24 hours to 4 days, leading the government to \"making decisions based on old information\".<ref name=\"starbacklog\">{{cite web| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| title=Huge backlog in COVID-19 test results means Ontario is making decisions based on old information| date=March 18, 2020| first=Kevin| last=Donovan| url-status=live| archive-date=March 19, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319001515/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/18/huge-backlog-in-covid-19-test-results-means-ontario-is-making-decisions-based-on-old-information.html| access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The same story reported that the government's goal of performing 5,000 tests per day may be two weeks away.<ref name=\"starbacklog\"/> The province was only able to process around 2,000 tests per day by March 19, which caused the backlog.<ref name=\"urlConcerns grow over slow pace of COVID-19 testing in Ontario | CBC News\"/>\n\nThe backlog increased to over 8,000 unprocessed samples on March 24 with patients waiting at least four days for results, partially due to fact that private and university laboratories are not allowed to process samples.<ref name=\"urlWhy Ontarios COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus | CBC News\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |title=Why Ontario's COVID-19 testing underestimates the spread of the virus &#124; CBC News |format= |work= |accessdate=2020-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324171047/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid19-ontario-coronavirus-positive-tests-cases-1.5507211 |archive-date=March 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ontario.ca/page/2019-novel-coronavirus The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)]\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=1cWm99ZSIeceKzu97rk50ik32cSvvX4pa&ll=44.45836936528724%2C-79.37585575178662&z=8 Map of COVID-19 cases and related closures at a regional level across Canada]\n*[http://covidcanada.ca/?p=ON Covid Canada] - Graph of data for spread of virus in Ontario and live news feed.\n*[https://dynamicmt.com/COVID-19-ON Chart of COVID-19 daily case count for Ontario]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{portalbar|Medicine|Ontario|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada by province or territory|Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ontario|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Mindmatrix", "label": "safe", "comment": "tweaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Ontario"}
{"title_page": "Battle of al-Mada'in", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n |partof=\n |image= File:Iraq Ninth Century.png\n |image_size = 300\n |caption=Iraq in the 9th/10th centuries\n |date=16\u201319 August 942\n |place=south of [[al-Mada'in]], modern-day [[Iraq]]\n |result=[[Hamdanid]] victory\n |combatant1= [[Hamdanid]] emirate of [[Mosul]]\n |combatant2= [[Baridis]] of [[Basra]]\n |commander1=[[Sayf al-Dawla]]<br>[[Tuzun (amir al-umara)|Tuzun]]<br>[[Khajkhaj]]\n |commander2=[[Abu'l-Husayn al-Baridi]]\n |strength1=\n |strength2=\n |casualties1=Heavy\n |casualties2=Heavy\n}}\nThe '''Battle of al-Mada'in''' was fought near [[al-Mada'in]] in central [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] between the armies of the [[Hamdanids]] and the [[Baridis]], for control over [[Baghdad]], the capital and seat of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] that was around {{Convert|22|km|mi|abbr=}} away. The Hamdanids had prior control of the Bagdhad. In a fiercely contested battle over four days (16\u201319 August 942) that cost both sides many casualties, the Hamdanid army prevailed. They were too exhausted to pursue, however, which allowed the Baridis to withdraw to [[Wasit]] and then [[Basra]].\n\n==Background==\nBy the 930s, after a series of civil wars that enfeebled its central government, the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] had splintered and shrunk to its core territories. Effective control over the more distant provinces of the empire had long been lost, but now autonomous local dynasties emerged in the territories around the Abbasids' metropolitan region of [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] itself: [[Medieval Egypt|Egypt]] and [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] came under the rule of the [[Ikhshidids]], the [[Hamdanids]] secured control over [[Upper Mesopotamia]], while most of [[Iran]] was ruled by [[Daylamite]] warlords, among whom the [[Buyids]] became prominent.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=194}} Even in Iraq itself, the authority of the caliphal government was challenged: in the south, around [[Basra]], the [[al-Baridi|Baridi]] family under [[Abu Abdallah al-Baridi]] established its own domain, more often than not withholding the tax revenues from Baghdad to fill their own coffers.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=194}}{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|pp=1046\u20131047}} These autonomous rulers vied with one another, and with military warlords from what remained of the Abbasid army, over control of [[Baghdad]], the administrative centre of Iraq and seat of the Abbasid caliphs. From 936 on, the caliphs were sidelined by a series of military dictators who enjoyed the title of {{Lang|ar-Latn|[[amir al-umara]]}}. A convoluted struggle for control of the office of {{Lang|ar-Latn|amir al-umara}}, and the figurehead caliphate with it, broke out among the various local rulers and the Turkish military chiefs, which would end in 946 with the victory of the Buyids.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=195\u2013196}}\n\nIn this turmoil, the Baridis managed to advance their positions from Basra to [[Wasit]], gain the support of the Daylamites in the Abbasid army, and briefly capture Baghdad for the first time in June 941.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|p=1046}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=366\u2013367, 370\u2013371}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=10, 12\u201318}} Although chased out of the capital by an uprising of the troops and the populace, in March 942 the Baridis managed to defeat the forces of the {{Lang|ar-Latn|amir al-umara}} [[Ibn Ra'iq]] and enter the capital once more.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|p=1046}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=374}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=25\u201326}} Ibn Ra'iq and Caliph [[al-Muttaqi]] fled north to [[Mosul]], ruled by the Hamdanids. The Hamdanid leader, Hasan, had Ibn Ra'iq murdered and was named by the Caliph {{Lang|ar-Latn|amir al-umara}} in his stead, with the {{Lang|ar-Latn|[[laqab]]}} (honorific epithet) of [[Nasir al-Dawla]] (\"Defender of the Dynasty\").{{Sfn|Denny|2015|p=405}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=374\u2013376}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=26, 29\u201330}} Baridi rule in Baghdad was tyrannical and chaotic, as the new rulers of the capital aimed only at extracting money; the city was rife with famine, disease, and lawlessness. Many of the [[Turkic peoples|Turkish]] officers in Ibn Ra'iq's employ who had previously defected to the Baridis, such as [[Tuzun (amir al-umara)|Tuzun]], plotted against the Baridi governor, Abu Abdallah's younger brother [[Abu'l-Husayn al-Baridi]]. When this was betrayed, they fled north for Mosul with many of their troops, where they encouraged the Caliph and the Hamdanids to campaign against Baghdad.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=27\u201328}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=376}}\n\n==Battle of al-Mada'in==\nAs the Hamdanids moved on Baghdad, Abu'l-Husayn abandoned the city and fled to Abu Abdallah in Wasit. The Hamdanids entered the city to a triumphal reception in mid-July 942.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=376}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=28, 30}} The situation was still in the balance, however, as Abu Abdallah gathered his forces at Wasit and began moving against the capital. Unease spread in Baghdad at the news, and the Caliph sent his harem upstream to [[Abbasid Samarra|Samarra]] for safety.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Command of the Hamdanid army was entrusted to Nasir al-Dawla's brother Ali, with the Turks under their own commanders Tuzun and [[Khajkhaj]], while the Baridi army was led by Abu'l-Husayn.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}}\n\nThe two armies met at the village of Gil, two [[parasangs]]\u2014{{circa|{{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=off}}}}\u2014south of [[al-Mada'in]].{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Al-Mada'in was in turn around {{Convert|22|km|mi|abbr=}} south of Baghdad.{{Sfn|Nicholson|2018|p=870}} The battle was fought over four days, 16\u201319 August 942. At first, the Baridis had the upper hand, and the Hamdanids were routed. Nasir al-Dawla managed to rally them at al-Mada'in, and defeat the Baridis.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Several high-ranking Baridi officials and commanders, including their army secretary, were captured; others defected to the Hamdanids, as did the entire Daylamite contingent in the Baridi army.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} On the other hand, so depleted and exhausted were the Hamdanids that they were unable to pursue the Baridis. Only a week later did they move on Wasit, where they found the Baridis gone for their stronghold of Basra.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=31\u201332}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=376\u2013377}} \n\nOn 2 September, Nasir al-Dawla staged a triumphal entry into Baghdad with the captive Baridi commanders, and al-Muttaqi awarded the {{Lang|ar-Latn|laqab}} of [[Sayf al-Dawla]] (\"Sword of the Dynasty\") to Ali, by which he was to become famous later as the [[emir]] of [[Aleppo]] and the champion of Islam against the Byzantines.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=32}}{{sfn|Bianquis|1997|p=104}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=270}} This double award to the Hamdanid brothers marked the first time that a {{Lang|ar-Latn|laqab}} incorporating the prestigious element ''[[al-Dawla]]'' was granted to anyone other than the [[vizier (Abbasid Caliphate)|vizier]], the Caliphate's chief minister.{{sfn|Bianquis|1997|p=104}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Hamdanid gold dinar, Nasir al-Dawla and Sayf al-Dawla.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Gold dinar]] minted at Baghdad in the name of [[Nasir al-Dawla]], 943]]\nThe costly victory at al-Mada'in was soon undone: while Sayf al-Dawla wanted to continue the campaign against the Baridis, his brother\u2014\"whether from jealousy or negligence\", according to historian Harold Bowen\u2014did not send him the funds requested. Furthermore, the two Turkish generals, Tuzun and Khajkhaj, began showing signs of insubordination. The growing unreliability of his army forced Sayf al-Dawla to abandon the campaign and secretly flee to Baghdad. Nasir al-Dawla, dismayed at these developments and exposed far from his real power-base, decided to give up the capital, and in June 943, the two brothers returned to Mosul.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=377\u2013378}} After Sayf al-Dawla left, Tuzun and Khajkhaj agreed to divide the spoils: Tuzun would become {{Lang|ar-Latn|amir al-umara}}, with Khajkhaj as commander-in-chief; but soon Tuzun had his colleague blinded and sidelined.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=382}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=43\u201347}} \n\nAfter becoming the master of Baghdad, Tuzun pursued a peace with the Baridis of Basra, sealed with a marriage alliance.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=382\u2013383}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=49\u201350}} The alliance between Tuzun and the Baridis was seen as a threat by Caliph al-Muttaqi and his advisors. In September 943, while Tuzun was still in Wasit, the caliph once more appealed to the Hamdanids for aid: an army under Nasir al-Dawla's cousin [[Abu Abdallah al-Husayn ibn al-Hasan|al-Husayn]] appeared before Baghdad, and the caliph left the capital and went north, meeting Nasir al-Dawla at [[Tikrit]].{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=383}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=52\u201354}} Tuzun immediately abandoned Wasit and pursued the caliph north, heavily defeated Sayf al-Dawla in two battles near Tikrit, and captured Mosul itself. An agreement was concluded between Tuzun and the Hamdanids on 26 May 944, whereby Nasir al-Dawla renounced his claims on the Caliphate's core lands in central Iraq, receiving in return recognition for his control over Upper Mesopotamia and his claims over [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]], in exchange for an annual tribute of 3.6 million [[Dirham|dirhams]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=270\u2013271}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=54\u201355}} \n\nTuzun's victory was concluded when al-Muttaqi was persuaded to return to the capital, only to be deposed and blinded, and [[al-Mustakfi]] placed in his stead.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=384\u2013385}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=196}} Tuzun's ascendancy did not last long, as almost immediately he had to face the attacks of the Buyids. When Tuzun himself died in 945, his secretary [[Muhammad ibn Shirzad]] tried to secure Hamdanid support, but to no avail. On 16 January 946, the Buyids captured Baghdad and inaugurated a century of Buyid rule over Baghdad.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=196, 214\u2013215}} The Baridis also faced mounting challenges at the same time: they had to defend Basra against the ruler of [[Oman proper|Oman]], and, their resources exhausted in the long contests for Baghdad, they now turned on one another. The youngest Baridi brother, Abu Yusuf, was assassinated by the eldest, Abu Abdallah, who in turn died in June 944. His son Abu'l-Qasim remained as ruler of Basra until the Buyids, following their capture of Baghdad, expelled him in 947.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|pp=1046\u20131047}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=383\u2013384}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Amedroz|editor1-first=Henry F.|editor1-link=Henry Frederick Amedroz|editor2-last=Margoliouth|editor2-first=David S.|title=The Eclipse of the \u2018Abbasid Caliphate. Original Chronicles of the Fourth Islamic Century, Vol. V: The concluding portion of The Experiences of Nations by Miskawaihi, Vol. II: Reigns of Muttaqi, Mustakfi, Muzi and Ta'i|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|pages=|year=1921|isbn=|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/eclipseofabbasid05ameduoft|oclc=13341177|ref=harv}}\n* {{EI2 | volume=9 | last = Bianquis | first = Thierry | authorlink = Thierry Bianquis | title=Sayf al-Dawla | pages = 103\u2013110 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_islam_COM_1010}}\n* {{cite book | first = Harold | last = Bowen | title = The Life and Times of \u02bfAl\u00ed Ibn \u02bf\u00cds\u00e0, \u2018The Good Vizier\u2019 | year = 1928 | location = Cambridge | publisher = Cambridge University Press | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TZM3AAAAIAAJ | oclc = 982525160 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Denny|first=Frederick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5h2aCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA405|title=An Introduction to Islam|date=2015-09-21|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-34727-9|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Nicholson|first=Oliver|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A09WDwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=%22al-madain%22+OR%22al-mada'in%22+%2225+miles%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity|date=2018-04-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-256246-3|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates|edition = Second}}\n* {{EI2  | last = Sourdel | first = Dominique | authorlink = Dominique Sourdel | volume=1 | title=al-Bar\u012bd\u012b | pages = 1046\u20131047 | url = http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_islam_SIM_1234}}\n\n{{coord missing|Iraq}}\n\n[[Category:942]]\n[[Category:940s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Abbasid Caliphate|Mada'in]]\n[[Category:Hamdanid emirate of Mosul]]\n[[Category:Iraq under the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Battles of Sayf al-Dawla|Mada'in]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n |partof=\n |image= File:Iraq Ninth Century.png\n |image_size = 300\n |caption=Iraq in the 9th/10th centuries\n |date=16\u201319 August 942\n |place=south of [[al-Mada'in]], modern-day [[Iraq]]\n |result=[[Hamdanid]] victory\n |combatant1= [[Hamdanid]] emirate of [[Mosul]]\n |combatant2= [[Baridis]] of [[Basra]]\n |commander1=[[Sayf al-Dawla]]<br>[[Tuzun (amir al-umara)|Tuzun]]<br>[[Khajkhaj]]\n |commander2=[[Abu'l-Husayn al-Baridi]]\n |strength1=\n |strength2=\n |casualties1=Heavy\n |casualties2=Heavy\n}}\nThe '''Battle of al-Mada'in''' was fought near [[al-Mada'in]] in central [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] between the armies of the [[Hamdanids]] and the [[Baridis]], for control over [[Baghdad]], the capital and seat of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] that was around {{Convert|22|km|mi|abbr=}} away. The Hamdanids had prior control of the Bagdhad. In a fiercely contested battle over four days (16\u201319 August 942) that cost both sides many casualties, the Hamdanid army prevailed. They were too exhausted to pursue, however, which allowed the Baridis to withdraw to [[Wasit]] and then [[Basra]].\n\n==Background==\nBy the 930s, after a series of civil wars that enfeebled its central government, the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] had splintered and shrunk to its core territories. Effective control over the more distant provinces of the empire had long been lost, but now autonomous local dynasties emerged in the territories around the Abbasids' metropolitan region of [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] itself: [[Medieval Egypt|Egypt]] and [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] came under the rule of the [[Ikhshidids]], the [[Hamdanids]] secured control over [[Upper Mesopotamia]], while most of [[Iran]] was ruled by [[Daylamite]] warlords, among whom the [[Buyids]] became prominent.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=194}} Even in Iraq itself, the authority of the caliphal government was challenged: in the south, around [[Basra]], the [[al-Baridi|Baridi]] family under [[Abu Abdallah al-Baridi]] established its own domain, more often than not withholding the tax revenues from Baghdad to fill their own coffers.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=194}}{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|pp=1046\u20131047}} These autonomous rulers vied with one another, and with military warlords from what remained of the Abbasid army, over control of [[Baghdad]], the administrative centre of Iraq and seat of the Abbasid caliphs. From 936 on, the caliphs were sidelined by a series of military dictators who enjoyed the title of {{Lang|ar|[[amir al-umara]]}}. A convoluted struggle for control of the office of ''{{Lang|ar|amir al-umara}}'', and the figurehead caliphate with it, broke out among the various local rulers and the Turkish military chiefs, which would end in 946 with the victory of the Buyids.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=195\u2013196}}\n\nIn this turmoil, the Baridis managed to advance their positions from Basra to [[Wasit]], gain the support of the Daylamites in the Abbasid army, and briefly capture Baghdad for the first time in June 941.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|p=1046}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=366\u2013367, 370\u2013371}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=10, 12\u201318}} Although chased out of the capital by an uprising of the troops and the populace, in March 942 the Baridis managed to defeat the forces of the ''{{Lang|ar|amir al-umara}}'' [[Ibn Ra'iq]] and enter the capital once more.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|p=1046}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=374}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=25\u201326}} Ibn Ra'iq and Caliph [[al-Muttaqi]] fled north to [[Mosul]], ruled by the Hamdanids. The Hamdanid leader, Hasan, had Ibn Ra'iq murdered and was named by the Caliph ''{{Lang|ar|amir al-umara}}'' in his stead, with the {{Lang|ar|[[laqab]]}} (honorific epithet) of [[Nasir al-Dawla]] (\"Defender of the Dynasty\").{{Sfn|Denny|2015|p=405}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=195\u2013196}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=374\u2013376}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=26, 29\u201330}} Baridi rule in Baghdad was tyrannical and chaotic, as the new rulers of the capital aimed only at extracting money; the city was rife with famine, disease, and lawlessness. Many of the [[Turkic peoples|Turkish]] officers in Ibn Ra'iq's employ who had previously defected to the Baridis, such as [[Tuzun (amir al-umara)|Tuzun]], plotted against the Baridi governor, Abu Abdallah's younger brother [[Abu'l-Husayn al-Baridi]]. When this was betrayed, they fled north for Mosul with many of their troops, where they encouraged the Caliph and the Hamdanids to campaign against Baghdad.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=27\u201328}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=376}}\n\n==Battle of al-Mada'in==\nAs the Hamdanids moved on Baghdad, Abu'l-Husayn abandoned the city and fled to Abu Abdallah in Wasit. The Hamdanids entered the city to a triumphal reception in mid-July 942.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=376}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=28, 30}} The situation was still in the balance, however, as Abu Abdallah gathered his forces at Wasit and began moving against the capital. Unease spread in Baghdad at the news, and the Caliph sent his harem upstream to [[Abbasid Samarra|Samarra]] for safety.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Command of the Hamdanid army was entrusted to Nasir al-Dawla's brother Ali, with the Turks under their own commanders Tuzun and [[Khajkhaj]], while the Baridi army was led by Abu'l-Husayn.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}}\n\nThe two armies met at the village of Gil, two [[parasangs]]\u2014{{circa|{{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=off}}}}\u2014south of [[al-Mada'in]].{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Al-Mada'in was in turn around {{Convert|22|km|mi|abbr=}} south of Baghdad.{{Sfn|Nicholson|2018|p=870}} The battle was fought over four days, 16\u201319 August 942. At first, the Baridis had the upper hand, and the Hamdanids were routed. Nasir al-Dawla managed to rally them at al-Mada'in, and defeat the Baridis.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} Several high-ranking Baridi officials and commanders, including their army secretary, were captured; others defected to the Hamdanids, as did the entire Daylamite contingent in the Baridi army.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=31}} On the other hand, so depleted and exhausted were the Hamdanids that they were unable to pursue the Baridis. Only a week later did they move on Wasit, where they found the Baridis gone for their stronghold of Basra.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=31\u201332}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=376\u2013377}} \n\nOn 2 September, Nasir al-Dawla staged a triumphal entry into Baghdad with the captive Baridi commanders, and al-Muttaqi awarded the ''{{Lang|ar|laqab}}'' of [[Sayf al-Dawla]] (\"Sword of the Dynasty\") to Ali, by which he was to become famous later as the [[emir]] of [[Aleppo]] and the champion of Islam against the Byzantines.{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|p=32}}{{sfn|Bianquis|1997|p=104}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=270}} This double award to the Hamdanid brothers marked the first time that a ''{{Lang|ar|laqab}}'' incorporating the prestigious element ''[[al-Dawla]]'' was granted to anyone other than the [[vizier (Abbasid Caliphate)|vizier]], the Caliphate's chief minister.{{sfn|Bianquis|1997|p=104}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Hamdanid gold dinar, Nasir al-Dawla and Sayf al-Dawla.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Gold dinar]] minted at Baghdad in the name of [[Nasir al-Dawla]], 943]]\nThe costly victory at al-Mada'in was soon undone: while Sayf al-Dawla wanted to continue the campaign against the Baridis, his brother\u2014\"whether from jealousy or negligence\", according to historian Harold Bowen\u2014did not send him the funds requested. Furthermore, the two Turkish generals, Tuzun and Khajkhaj, began showing signs of insubordination. The growing unreliability of his army forced Sayf al-Dawla to abandon the campaign and secretly flee to Baghdad. Nasir al-Dawla, dismayed at these developments and exposed far from his real power-base, decided to give up the capital, and in June 943, the two brothers returned to Mosul.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=377\u2013378}} After Sayf al-Dawla left, Tuzun and Khajkhaj agreed to divide the spoils: Tuzun would become ''{{Lang|ar|amir al-umara}}'', with Khajkhaj as commander-in-chief; but soon Tuzun had his colleague blinded and sidelined.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=382}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=43\u201347}} \n\nAfter becoming the master of Baghdad, Tuzun pursued a peace with the Baridis of Basra, sealed with a marriage alliance.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=382\u2013383}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=49\u201350}} The alliance between Tuzun and the Baridis was seen as a threat by Caliph al-Muttaqi and his advisors. In September 943, while Tuzun was still in Wasit, the caliph once more appealed to the Hamdanids for aid: an army under Nasir al-Dawla's cousin [[Abu Abdallah al-Husayn ibn al-Hasan|al-Husayn]] appeared before Baghdad, and the caliph left the capital and went north, meeting Nasir al-Dawla at [[Tikrit]].{{sfn|Bowen|1928|p=383}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=52\u201354}} Tuzun immediately abandoned Wasit and pursued the caliph north, heavily defeated Sayf al-Dawla in two battles near Tikrit, and captured Mosul itself. An agreement was concluded between Tuzun and the Hamdanids on 26 May 944, whereby Nasir al-Dawla renounced his claims on the Caliphate's core lands in central Iraq, receiving in return recognition for his control over Upper Mesopotamia and his claims over [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]], in exchange for an annual tribute of 3.6 million [[Dirham|dirhams]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=270\u2013271}}{{sfn|Amedroz|Margoliouth|1921|pp=54\u201355}} \n\nTuzun's victory was concluded when al-Muttaqi was persuaded to return to the capital, only to be deposed and blinded, and [[al-Mustakfi]] placed in his stead.{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=384\u2013385}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=196}} Tuzun's ascendancy did not last long, as almost immediately he had to face the attacks of the Buyids. When Tuzun himself died in 945, his secretary [[Muhammad ibn Shirzad]] tried to secure Hamdanid support, but to no avail. On 16 January 946, the Buyids captured Baghdad and inaugurated a century of Buyid rule over Baghdad.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|pp=196, 214\u2013215}} The Baridis also faced mounting challenges at the same time: they had to defend Basra against the ruler of [[Oman proper|Oman]], and, their resources exhausted in the long contests for Baghdad, they now turned on one another. The youngest Baridi brother, Abu Yusuf, was assassinated by the eldest, Abu Abdallah, who in turn died in June 944. His son Abu'l-Qasim remained as ruler of Basra until the Buyids, following their capture of Baghdad, expelled him in 947.{{sfn|Sourdel|1960|pp=1046\u20131047}}{{sfn|Bowen|1928|pp=383\u2013384}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Amedroz|editor1-first=Henry F.|editor1-link=Henry Frederick Amedroz|editor2-last=Margoliouth|editor2-first=David S.|title=The Eclipse of the \u2018Abbasid Caliphate. Original Chronicles of the Fourth Islamic Century, Vol. V: The concluding portion of The Experiences of Nations by Miskawaihi, Vol. II: Reigns of Muttaqi, Mustakfi, Muzi and Ta'i|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|pages=|year=1921|isbn=|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/eclipseofabbasid05ameduoft|oclc=13341177|ref=harv}}\n* {{EI2 | volume=9 | last = Bianquis | first = Thierry | authorlink = Thierry Bianquis | title=Sayf al-Dawla | pages = 103\u2013110 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_islam_COM_1010}}\n* {{cite book | first = Harold | last = Bowen | title = The Life and Times of \u02bfAl\u00ed Ibn \u02bf\u00cds\u00e0, \u2018The Good Vizier\u2019 | year = 1928 | location = Cambridge | publisher = Cambridge University Press | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TZM3AAAAIAAJ | oclc = 982525160 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Denny|first=Frederick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5h2aCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA405|title=An Introduction to Islam|date=2015-09-21|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-34727-9|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Nicholson|first=Oliver|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A09WDwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&dq=%22al-madain%22+OR%22al-mada'in%22+%2225+miles%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity|date=2018-04-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-256246-3|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates|edition = Second}}\n* {{EI2  | last = Sourdel | first = Dominique | authorlink = Dominique Sourdel | volume=1 | title=al-Bar\u012bd\u012b | pages = 1046\u20131047 | url = http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_islam_SIM_1234}}\n\n{{coord missing|Iraq}}\n\n[[Category:942]]\n[[Category:940s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Abbasid Caliphate|Mada'in]]\n[[Category:Hamdanid emirate of Mosul]]\n[[Category:Iraq under the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Battles of Sayf al-Dawla|Mada'in]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix lang templates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_al-Mada%27in"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Bulgaria}}\n{{pp|dispute|small=yes}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria\n| map1            = COVID-19_Outbreak_cases_in_Bulgaria.png\n| legend1         = <center>Number of confirmed cases by province <br/> (as of 3 April)<ref name=\"ESRI\">{{cite web|url=https://esribulgaria.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/6e2c968cf38540f29a4311295dce390f|title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 COVID-19 \u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|date=28 March 2020|website=ESRI Bulgaria: COVID-19 Tracker|language=bg-BG|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref></center> {{legend|#fefeea|0 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|1\u20139 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|10\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|51\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|100+ confirmed}}\n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case      = [[Pleven]], [[Gabrovo]]\n| arrival_date    = 8 March 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] (globally)<br />local source unknown\n| deaths          = 14\n| website         = [https://www.mh.government.bg/bg/informaciya-za-grazhdani/informaciya-otnosno-noviya-koronavirus-2019-ncov/ Bulgarian Ministry of Health]\n| confirmed_cases = 485\n| recovery_cases  = 30\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Bulgaria]] when the country's first case was confirmed on 8 March 2020. As of 3 April 2020, there are 485 confirmed cases in 23 out of 28 Bulgarian provinces, with 14 recorded deaths and 30 recoveries. A total of 6454 PCR tests had been performed by 26 March.\n\n== Background ==\nA National Crisis-management Staff was formed by the Bulgarian government on 5 March to deal with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0421\u043f\u0435\u0448\u043d\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0430 \u0438 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 (\u041e\u0411\u0417\u041e\u0420) |url=https://nova.bg/news/view/2020/02/24/279057/%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%88%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%BC%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%89%D1%83-%D0%BA%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D0%B0-%D0%B8-%D1%83-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%B7%D0%BE%D1%80/ |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> The Government has appointed [[Major general|Major General]] [[Professor]] Doctor [[Ventsislav Mutafchiyski]] as the Chairman of the Staff. MG Prof. Dr. Mutafchiyski is the Director of the [[Military Medical Academy (Bulgaria)|Military Medical Academy]] and the most senior medical officer of the [[Bulgarian Armed Forces]]. The MMA combines the military medical services of the country in their entirety with several hospitals in the capital Sofia and around the country. At the same time it is one of the country's leading medical institutions and possesses large medical treatment capacity and know-how. The Staff fulfills a direct operational role in the management of the crisis and its decisions are implemented through executive orders of [[Prime Minister of Bulgaria|Bulgaria's Prime Minister]] and the country's Minister of Health.\n\nOn 23 March a separate Medical Council for dealing with the coronavirus pandemic was appointed by the Prime Minister. The Council is chaired by Professor [[Kosta Kostov]], a leading pulmonary disease expert. The Council's mission is to provide the government with complementary analysis and action proposals and the general public with professional guidance and information. Unlike the National Crisis-management Staff, which is a formal national institution with executive power and tasks, the Council has mostly a knowledge-based advisory role.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u044f\u0442 \u0441\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0449\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0435 \u0441 COVID-19 |url=https://btvnovinite.bg/bulgaria/prof-kostov-medicinskijat-savet-shte-raboti.html}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== 8 March ===\nOn 8 March 2020 [[Bulgaria]] confirmed its first two cases, a 27-year-old man from [[Pleven]] and a 75-year-old woman from [[Gabrovo]]. Neither of the two reported having traveled to areas with known coronavirus cases. The man tested positive for the virus after being hospitalized for a respiratory infection, and authorities announced plans to test several people who were in contact with the two individuals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/bulgaria-confirms-coronavirus-cases-amid-flu-outbreak/30475539.html|title=Bulgaria, Moldova Report First Coronavirus Cases |date=8 March 2020|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]}}</ref> Two other samples in Pleven and Gabrovo were found positive on 8 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/08/2754995/prof-todor-kantardzhiev-ot-pleven-imame-dve-polozhitelni-probi-za-koronavirus-ot-gabrovo-sashto.html|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444. \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432: \u041e\u0442 \u041f\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0438\u043c\u0430\u043c\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441, \u043e\u0442 \u0413\u0430\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u044a\u0449\u043e|language=Bulgarian|date=8 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> [[Index case|Patient zero]] remains unknown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.actualno.com/healthy/oficialno-ima-chetiri-potvyrdeni-sluchaja-na-koronavirus-v-bylgarija-news_1440246.html|title=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e: \u0418\u043c\u0430 \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0432\u044a\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|date=8 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, the hospital in Gabrovo requested additional personnel from other hospitals in the country, as it only had three [[communicable disease]]s specialists. All of its [[internal medicine]] specialists have been quarantined after one of the four initial cases was confirmed to be a nurse at the hospital.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u0430\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 Covid-19 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/gabrovo-poiska-podkreplenie-ot-infektsionisti-zaradi-dvata-sluchaya-na-covid-19 |accessdate=8 March 2020 |date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The government issued a nationwide ban on closed-door public events.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/politika/pravitelstvoto-zabrani-vsichki-masovi-proyavi-na-zakrito-v-stranata |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> The origin of the outbreak remains unknown, and the [[Ministry of Interior (Bulgaria)|Ministry of Interior]] is tracking down all individuals who have been in contact with the patients.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0427\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 COVID-19 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=http://www.vma.bg/newsitem.html?action=news&newsid=829 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> As of 8 March, 254 suspected cases were under quarantine across the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0414\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0430: 254 \u0441\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0430 \u0432 \u0446\u044f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430 |url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/08/2755023/ministar-denitsa-sacheva-254-sa-bolnichnite-listove-s-karantina-za-koronavirusa-v-tsyalata-strana.html |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 10 March ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Bulgaria medical cases chart}}\nTwo additional cases were confirmed in Sofia on 10 March 2020: a 74-year-old man and his 66-year-old wife. Both have arrived from [[Lom, Bulgaria|Lom]] two weeks prior to admission.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430 \u043e\u0449\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 - \u0432 \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u0441\u044a\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0439\u043a\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/za-oshte-dva-sluchaya-na-noviya-virus-u-nas-v-sofiya-saobshti-boyko-borisov |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0432 \"\u041f\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432\" \u0435 \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0442\u043d\u0430, \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0432\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u0433\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/pirogov-e-izoliran-zaradi-dvamata-novi-zarazeni-borisov-svikva-saveta-za-sigurnost |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The woman died on the next day, becoming the first COVID-19 victim in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432\u0437\u0435 \u043f\u044a\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0436\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/11/4039345_koronavirusut_vze_purva_jertva_v_bulgariia/ |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 11 March ===\nA suspected case of a 33-year-old man was reported by the Saint George Hospital in [[Plovdiv]] on 11 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=33-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0435\u043d \u043c\u044a\u0436 \u043e\u0442 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e \u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0418\u043d\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u041c\u0411\u0410\u041b \"\u0421\u0432. \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\" \u0432 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0434\u0438\u0432 \u0441\u044a\u0441 \u0441\u044a\u043c\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 |url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/11/2756041/33-godishen-mazh-ot-selo-kadievo-e-priet-v-infektsioznata-klinika-na-umbal-sv-georgi-v-plovdiv-sas-samnenie-za-koronavirus.html |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, a 40-year-old woman in [[Varna]] showed COVID-19 symptoms on [[CT scan]], although regional health authorities have not yet confirmed the case.<ref>{{cite news |title=40-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044a\u0432 \u0412\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430, \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0442 - \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 |url=https://www.dnes.bg/stranata/2020/03/11/40-godishna-pripadna-vyv-varna-predpolagat-koronavirus.441831 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 12 March ===\nBy 12 March, the number of cases had increased to 23, most of them in Sofia. Many of these had been in contact with the elderly couple admitted to the [[Pirogov Hospital]] on 10 March.\n\n=== 13 March ===\nOn 13 March, after 16 reported cases in one day, Bulgaria declared a state of emergency for one month until 13 April. Schools, shopping centres, cinemas, restaurants, and other places of business were closed. All sports events were suspended. Only supermarkets, food markets, pharmacies, banks and gas stations remain open.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nova.bg/news/view/2020/03/13/281109/\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u0432-\u0438\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435-\u0437\u0430-1-\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0446 |title=\u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 1 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0446 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Focus |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally, all arrivals from Italy, Spain, Iran, South Korea and China were placed under a mandatory 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0412\u043d\u0420: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0435 \u0435 \u0432\u044a\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u044a\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438 |url=https://www.bgonair.bg/a/2-bulgaria/188624-mvnr-balgariya-ne-e-vavela-ogranicheniya-na-darzhavnite-si-granitsi |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> There were 13 breaches of quarantine; patients involved were returned to treatment facilities and warned of repercussions, including fines and prison sentences.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u043d: 13 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u0441\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0438\u0437\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442 \u0433\u0438 |url=https://dariknews.bg/novini/bylgariia/samo-za-den-13-dushi-sa-narushili-zadylzhitelnata-karantina-izdirvat-gi-video-2216674 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 14 March ===\nOn 14 March, a second death and a third case in Pleven were reported. The second victim of the virus was the 74-year old husband of the first victim.<ref>[https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/14/4040910_vtora_jertva_na_koronavirusa_i_10_novi_zarazeni/ www.dnevnik.bg]</ref>\n\n=== 15 March ===\nThe number of confirmed cases in Bulgaria rose to 51 on 15 March. A total of 83 tests were done at the Military Medical Academy, of which six were positive, and 51 were processed at the National Reference Laboratory, of which two were positive. In Varna, one test out of 12 samples proved positive.\n\n=== 16 March ===\nThe Ministry of Health announced that citizens from a number of countries would be prohibited from entering Bulgaria starting 00:00 on 18 March. These are China, Iran, Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Spain, Italy, South Korea, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Switzerland and the United Kingdom. Additionally, sanitary control units will be established on some border crossings with Serbia, North Macedonia, Greece and Romania.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434 \u0437\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0432\u0430 \u0432\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430 15 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438! |url=https://www.dnes.bg/obshtestvo/2020/03/16/nova-zapoved-zabraniava-vlizane-u-nas-na-grajdani-na-15-strani.442422 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> The number of total cases rose to 62, including two British citizens vacationing in [[Bansko]].\n\n=== 17 March ===\n81 cases were reported, several linked to an outbreak in Bansko. None of the patients were in critical condition.<ref>{{cite news |title=81 \u0441\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/81-sa-veche-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-v-balgariya |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 18 March ===\nThe total number of cases increased to 94 by 18 March, with new cases appearing in [[Smolyan]], [[Veliko Tarnovo]] and [[Pernik]] among recent arrivals from outside the country. The previous day, Bansko became the first town in the country to be put under quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438, \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0441\u0442\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044f\u043d \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e \u0422\u044a\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/11-novi-polozhitelni-probi-virusat-stigna-smolyan-i-veliko-tarnovo |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0430\u0439\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d \u0441\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u043e\u0442 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/mayka-i-sin-sa-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-ot-pernik |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 19 March ===\nOn 19 March the cases rose to 105 and an 80-year-old woman, who recently had a stroke, died from COVID-19 on the same day, making her the third victim from the disease in Bulgaria.\n\n=== 20 March ===\nThe total number of cases increased to 127 and the first recovery occurred.\n\n=== 21 March ===\nThe number of cases increased to 142 by noon, and three patients had recovered. Two cities, [[Dobrich]] and [[Shumen]], confirmed their first cases, the latter related to the Bansko cluster. There are 84 male and 58 female patients, the youngest being 4 years old, and the oldest 81 years old. More than 5,000 tests had been carried out, and an additional 10,000 tests would be made available at short notice.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u0435\u043d. \u041c\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0444\u0447\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438: 142 \u0441\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 (\u0412\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e) |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/21/4044105_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_izvunrednoto_polojenie/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020 |publisher=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0418\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0442\u043d\u043e \u0449\u0435 \u0441\u0435 \u0443\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0438, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432}}\n</ref>\n\n=== 24 March ===\nThe cases increased to 218 and the first case in Stara Zagora province was confirmed. A man from the town of [[Kazanlak]] was admitted in the Infectious unit in the hospital in [[Stara Zagora]]. He is believed to be 60 years old and returned from France on the 14th of March.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0441\u0430 218, \u043f\u044a\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u0432 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430 |url=https://www.bgonair.bg/a/2-bulgaria/189351-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-u-nas-veche-sa-218-parvi-sluchai-v-stara-zagora |publisher= Bulgaria ON AIR |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 25 March ===\nThe number of cases increased to 242 by the end of the day, with the city of [[Sliven]] reporting its first confirmed case. 16 new cases with no relation between them were registered in Sofia, with some being medical staff from a local hospital. Two new cases were confirmed in [[Blagoevgrad]], two in Plovdiv and one in Pleven. Two of the patients who were in critical condition were stabilized but remain \"in stable but severe condition\". One recovered completely, bringing the number of total recoveries to 5.\n\n=== 26 March ===\nA total of 22 cases were reported, bringing the overall number to 264. The coronavirus were registered for the first time in [[Kardzhali]] and [[Haskovo]]. 15 of the newly confirmed cases were in Sofia, 2 in Smolyan, one in Pleven, one in Veliko Tarnovo and one in Varna. Two people were admitted to hospital in critical condition, while three new patients recovered, bringing the number of recovered to 8. Two soldiers were confirmed to have be infected - one was stationed in Kosovo and was immediately brought back to Sofia, and the other contracted the virus in Romania, where he was hospitalised. The national quarantine was extended by additional two weeks and is now expected to finish on April 12.\n\n=== 27 March ===\n29 new cases were registered, with the total number reaching 293. From these, 17 were in Sofia, 5 in Plovdiv, 3 in [[Burgas]], and one each in Varna, [[Kyustendil]], Sliven and [[Pazardzhik]]. At least 93 people remained hospitalized, with 53 in Sofia alone.\n\n=== 28 March ===\nThe total number of cases reached 331, an increase of 38 from the previous day. The new cases included 19 in Sofia, 5 in Blagoevgrad, 4 in Burgas, 3 in Varna, 2 each in Kardzhali, Plovdiv and Shumen, and 1 in Smolyan. Four new deaths were also reported, with two occurring in Blagoevgrad and one each in Kyustendil and Sofia.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0434\u043e 331 (\u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044f) |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/28/4047390_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_zarazenite_narasnaha_do_331/ |publisher=Dnevnik |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 29 March ===\nA total of 15 new cases were reported, with 8 in Sofia, 3 in Plovdiv, and one each in Kardzhali, Sliven, Smolyan and Varna. Three new recoveries were also announced, while the number of deaths rose to 8 after a 51-year-old woman died in the Blagoevgrad hospital, one day after her mother had succumbed to the virus. The Ministry of Health announced that 125 out of 324 active cases remain hospitalized, with 13 of those in serious condition. The total number of tests performed exceeded 7,000, with 276 done on 29 March alone.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0445\u0430 346 |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/29/4047568_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_zarazenite_stanaha_346/ |publisher=Dnevnik |date=29 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 30 March ===\nThirteen new cases were reported, with seven in Sofia and one each in Blagoevgrad, Kardzhali, Montana, Pleven, Plovdiv and Sliven, for a total of 359 cases. 113 patients remained hospitalized, with 13 in serious condition. Around 56% of all those infected so far were male versus 44% female, with a median age of 45. The total number of recoveries rose to 17.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0430 359, \u043d\u044f\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/30/4048177_zarazenite_v_bulgariia_sa_359_niama_sluchai_v_novi/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n=== 31 March ===\nThe total number of confirmed infections increased by 40 to 399, and the first two cases were reported from the province of [[Silistra Province|Silistra]]. 20 of the new cases were registered in Sofia, four each in Burgas and Kyustendil, three each in Plovdiv and Varna, two in Silistra, and one each in Kardzhali, Pernik, Shumen and Stara Zagora. The number of hospitalized patients increased to 146, with 14 in serious condition, while 20 medical workers were announced to have contracted the disease so far. No new deaths or recoveries were announced. From the total of 399 confirmed cases, just under 57% (227) were male, versus 43% (172) who were female.<ref>{{cite news |title=399 \u0441\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0432\u044a\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u043d\u0430 COVID-19 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441|url=https://www.mh.government.bg/bg/novini/aktualno/399-sa-potvrdenite-sluchai-na-covid-19-u-nas/ |publisher=Bulgarian Ministry of Health (mh.government.bg) |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n=== 1 April ===\nThe province of [[Ruse Province|Ruse]] reported its first case as part of 23 new infections across the country, bringing the total to 422. In addition to Ruse, 10 new cases were reported in Sofia, two each in Blagoevgrad, Burgas, Dobrich and Plovdiv, and one each in Haskovo, Kardzhali, Sliven and Stara Zagora. Two deaths were registered - a 57-year-old man in Kyustendil and a 40-year-old man in Sofia.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0418\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0449\u0435 \u0441\u0435 \u0443\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0438, \u0436\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0430 10 (\u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044f)|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/04/01/4048818_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_izvunrednoto_polojenie_shte/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref> [[Hassan Ademov]] from the [[Movement for Rights and Freedoms]] became the first Bulgarian [[Member of parliament|member of parliament]] to contract the virus, forcing the announcement of a mass test on 2 April that would cover government staff and all 240 MPs.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0414\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442 \u043e\u0442 \u0414\u041f\u0421 \u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/politika/2020/03/31/4048787_deputat_ot_dps_e_s_koronavirus/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n=== 2 April ===\nThe total number of infections increased by 35 to 457, with the first case being reported from the province of [[Vidin Province|Vidin]]. The new cases included 20 in Sofia, four in Smolyan, three in Varna, two in Dobrich, and one each in Blagoevgrad, Montana, Pazardzhik, Plovdiv, Veliko Tarnovo and Vidin. No new deaths were reported, while the number of recoveries reached 25. 179 patients were currently hospitalized, with 18 in intensive care.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u0430 458 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438, \u0431\u0435\u0437\u0432\u044a\u0437\u043c\u0435\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449 \u0437\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430 (\u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044f)|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/04/02/4049299_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_zarazeni_sa_458_dushi/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref> A further two MPs were among the new cases, both from the ruling [[GERB]] party, including their parliamentary group speaker Daniela Daritkova.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0414\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442 \u043e\u0442 \u0413\u0415\u0420\u0411 \u0441\u0430 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/politika/2020/04/02/4049397_daniela_daritkova_i_deputat_ot_gerb_sa_s_koronavirus/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n=== 3 April ===\nThe confirmed case count reached 487, after 28 new infections were registered - 18 in Sofia, two each in Plovdiv and Smolyan, and one each in Blagoevgrad, Burgas, Kardzhali, Kyustendil, Veliko Tarnovo and Vidin. Four deaths were also announced, with one occurring late on the previous evening in Stara Zagora.<ref name=\"DnevnikApr3\">{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0434\u043e 14 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/04/03/4049902_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_pochinalite_narasnaha_do_14/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref> Male patients continued to account for just under 57% of all cases (versus 43% female), with a median age of 47.<ref>{{cite news |title=485 \u0441\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0432\u044a\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u043d\u0430 COVID-19 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441|url=https://www.mh.government.bg/bg/novini/aktualno/485-sa-potvrdenite-sluchai-na-covid-19-u-nas/ |publisher=Bulgarian Ministry of Health (mh.government.bg) |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Cases ===\n{{Side box |metadata=No\n | above = '''Cases of coronavirus in Bulgaria'''\n | abovestyle = text-align:center\n | text = {{Graph:Chart\n  | type = line\n  | linewidth = 1\n  | showSymbols = 1\n  | width = 500\n  | height = 200\n  | showValues = offset:4\n  | xAxisTitle = Date\n  | xAxisAngle = -40\n  | x =8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr\n  | yAxisTitle = No. of cases\n  | y1 = 4